@node Introduction, Getting Started, Top, Top
@chapter Introduction

SB-Prolog is a Prolog system based on an extension of the Warren Abstract Machine
@cite{D.H.D. Warren, ``An Abstract Prolog Instruction Set,'' Tech. Note 309, SRI
International, 1983}. The WAM simulator is written in C to enhance portability.  Prolog
source programs can be compiled into byte code files, which contain encodings of WAM
instructions and are interpreted by the simulator.  Programs can also be interpreted via
consult.@REFILL

SB-Prolog offers several features  that  are  not  found  on  most  Prolog  systems
currently  available.   These  include:  compilation to object files; dynamic loading of
predicates; provision for generating executable code on the global stack, which  can  be
later  be  reclaimed; an extension table facility that permits memoization of relations.
Other features include full integration between compiled and  interpreted  code,  and  a
facility  for  the  definition and expansion of macros that is fully compatible with the
runtime system.@REFILL

The system incorporates tail recursion optimization, and performs  clause  indexing
in  both  compiled and interpreted code.  However, there is no garbage collector for the
global stack.  This may be incorporated into a later version.@REFILL

One of the few luxuries afforded to a person giving software away for free  is  the
ability to take philosophical stances without hurting his wallet.  Based on our faith in
the ``declarative ideal'', viz. that pure programs with declarative readings  are  Good,
we have attempted to encourage, where possible, a more declarative style of programming.
To this end, we have deliberately chosen to not reward programs containing cuts in  some
situations  where more declarative code is possible (@pxref{Efficiency},
@pxref{Adding Builtins}).  We have also resisted the temptation to make assert less expensive.
We hope this will help promote a better programming style.@REFILL

@node Getting Started, Syntax, Introduction, Top
@chapter Getting Started

This section is intended to give a broad overview of the  SB-Prolog  system,  so  as  to
enable  the  new  user  to  begin using the system with a minimum of delay.  Many of the
topics touched on here are covered in greater depth in later sections.@REFILL

@menu
* Dynamic Loader Search Path::
* System Directories::
* Invoking the Simulator::
* Executing Programs::
* Execution Directives::
@end menu

@node Dynamic Loader Search Path, System Directories, , Getting Started
@section The Dynamic Loader Search Path

In SB-Prolog, it is not necessary for the user to load all the predicates necessary to
execute a program.  Instead, if an undefined predicate @code{foo} is encountered during
execution, the system searches the user's directories in the order specified by the
environment variable @code{SIMPATH} until it finds a directory containing a file @file{foo} whose name
is that of the undefined predicate.  It then dynamically loads and links the file @file{foo}
(which is expected to be a byte code file defining the predicate @code{foo}), and continues
with execution; if no such file can be found, an error message is given and execution
fails.  This feature makes it unnecessary for the user to have to explicitly link in all
the predicates that might be necessary in a program: instead, only those files are
loaded  which  are necessary to have the program execute.  This can significantly reduce
the memory requirements of programs.@REFILL

The key to this dynamic search-and-load behaviour is the @code{SIMPATH} environment
variable, which specifies the order in which directories are to be searched.  It may be
set by adding the following line to the user's @file{.cshrc} file:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{setenv SIMPATH} @i{path}

where @i{path} is a sequence of directory names separated by colons:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{dir<1>:dir<2>: ... :dir<n>}

and @code{dir<i>} are full path names to the respective directories.   For  example,  executing
the command @REFILL

@CENTER @t{setenv SIMPATH .:$HOME/prolog/modlib:$HOME/prolog/lib}

sets the search order for undefined predicates to the following: first, the directory in
which the program is executing is searched; if the appropriate file is not found in this
directory, the directories searched are, in order, @file{~/prolog/modlib} and
@file{~/prolog/lib}.  If the appropriate file is not found in any of these directories,
the system gives an error message and execution fails.@REFILL

The beginning user is advised to include the system directories (listed in the next
section) in his @code{SIMPATH}, in order to be able to access the system libraries.@REFILL

@node System Directories, Invoking the Simulator, Dynamic Loader Search Path, Getting Started
@section System Directories

There are four basic system directories: @file{cmplib}, @file{lib}, @file{modlib} and
@file{sim}.  @file{cmplib} contains the Prolog to byte code translator; @file{lib} and @file{modlib}
contain library routines.  The @file{src} subdirectory in each of these contains the
corresponding Prolog source programs.  The directory @file{sim} contains the simulator, the
subdirectory @file{builtin} contains code for the builtin predicates of the system. It is
recommended that the beginning user include the system directories in his @code{SIMPATH},
by setting @code{SIMPATH} to @file{.:SBP/modlib:SBP/lib:SBP/cmplib} where @file{SBP}
denotes the path to the root of the SB-Prolog system directories.@REFILL

@node Invoking the Simulator, Executing Programs, System Directories, Getting Started
@section Invoking the Simulator

The simulator is invoked by the command ``@t{sbprolog} @i{bc_file}'' where
@i{bc_file} is a byte code file resulting from the compilation of a Prolog program.
In almost all cases, the user will wish to interact with the SB-Prolog query evaluator,
in which case @i{bc_file} will be @file{$readloop}, and the command will be
``@t{sbprolog} @file{Path/$readloop}'' where @file{Path} is the path to the directory containing the
command interpreter @file{$readloop}. This directory, typically, is @file{modlib}
(@pxref{System Directories}).@REFILL

The command interpreter reads in a query typed in by the user, evaluates it and prints
the answer(s), repeating this until it encounters an end-of-file (the standard
end-of-file character on the system, e.g. @kbd{C-d}), or the user types in
@code{end_of_file} or @code{halt}.@REFILL

The user should ensure that the the directory containing the executable file @file{sim}
(typically, the system directory @file{sim}: see @xref{System Directories}) is included
in the shell variable @code{path}; if not, the full path to the simulator will have to be
specified.@REFILL

In general, the simulator may be invoked with a variety of options, as
follows:@REFILL

@example
    sbprolog -options @file{bc_file}
@r{or}
    sbprolog -option<1> -option<2> ... -option<n> @file{bc_file}
@end example

The options recognized by the simulator are described elsewhere
(@pxref{Simulator Options}).@REFILL

When called with a byte code file @file{bc_file}, the simulator begins execution with  the
first  clause  in  that  file.   The first clause in such a file, therefore, should be a
clause without any arguments in the head  (otherwise,  the  simulator  will  attempt  to
dereference  argument pointers in the head that are really pointing into deep space, and
usually come to a sad end).  If the user is executing a file in this manner rather  than
using the command interpreter, he should also be careful to include the undefined predicate
handler, consisting of  the  predicates  @b{_$interrupt}/2  and  @b{_$undefined_pred}/1,
which is normally defined in the files @file{modlib/src/$init_sys.P} and
@file{modlib/src/$readloop}.@REFILL

@node Executing Programs, Execution Directives, Invoking the Simulator, Getting Started
@section Executing Programs

There are two ways of executing a program: a source file may be compiled into a
byte-code file, which can then be loaded and executed; or, the source file may be
interpreted via consult.  The system supports full integration of compiled and
interpreted code, so that some predicates of a program may be compiled, while others may
be interpreted.  However, the unit of compilation or consulting remains the file.  The
remainder of this section describes each of these procedures in more detail.@REFILL

@menu
* Compiling Programs::
* Loading Byte Code Files::
* Consulting Programs::
@end menu

@node Compiling Programs, Loading Byte Code Files, , Executing Programs
@subsection Compiling Programs

The compiler is invoked through the Prolog  predicate  @b{compile}.   It  translates  Prolog
source programs into byte code that can then be executed on the simulator.  The compiler
may be invoked as follows:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile(InFile [, OutFile ] [, OptionsList ]).
@r{or}
    | ?- compile(InFile, OutFile, OptionsList, PredList).
@end example

where optional parameters are enclosed in brackets.  @code{InFile} is the name of the input
(i.e.  source) file; @code{OutFile} is the name of the output file (i.e. byte code) file;
@code{OptionsList} is a list of compiler options, and @code{PredList} is a list of terms
P/N denoting the predicates defined in @code{InFile}, where P is a predicate name
and N its arity.@REFILL

The input and output file names must be Prolog atoms, i.e.  either begin with a lower
case letter and consist only of letters, digits, dollar signs and underscores; or, be
enclosed within single quotes.  If the output file name is not specified, it defaults to
@code{InFile.out}.  The list of options, if specified, is a Prolog list, i.e. a term of the
form:@REFILL

@CENTER [ option<1>, option<2>, ..., option<n> ].

If left unspecified, it defaults to the empty list @t{[]}.  @code{PredList}, if specified,
is  usually  given as an uninstantiated variable; its principal use is for setting trace points
on the predicates in the file (@pxref{Debugging} and @pxref{The Compiler}).  Notice  that
PredList  can  only appear in @b{compile}/4.@REFILL

A list of compiler options appears elsewhere (@pxref{Compiler Options}).

@node Loading Byte Code Files, Consulting Programs, Compiling Programs, Executing Programs
@subsection Loading Byte Code Files

Byte code files may be loaded into the simulator using the predicate @bb{load}:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- @b{load}(ByteCode_File).
@end example

where @code{ByteCode_File} is a Prolog atom (@pxref{Terms}) that is the name of a  byte  code
file.@REFILL

The @bb{load} predicate invokes the dynamic loader, which carries out a search according
to  the sequence specified by the environment variable @code{SIMPATH}
(@pxref{Dynamic Loader Search Path}).  It is therefore not necessary to always specify the
full path name to the file to be loaded.@REFILL

Byte code files may be concatenated together to  produce  other  byte  code  files.
Thus,  for  example, if @file{foo1} and @file{foo2} are byte code files resulting from the compilation
of two Prolog source programs, then the file @file{foo}, obtained by executing the  shell
command @REFILL

@CENTER @t{cat foo1 foo2 > foo}

is a byte code file as well, and may be loaded and executed.  In this case, loading  and
executing  the  file @file{foo} would give the same result as loading @file{foo1} and @file{foo2}
separately, which in turn would be the same as concatenating the original source files and compiling
this  larger  file.  This makes it easier to compile large programs: one need only break
them into smaller pieces, compile the individual pieces, and concatenate  the  resulting
byte code files together.@REFILL

@node Consulting Programs, , Loading Byte Code Files, Executing Programs
@subsection Consulting Programs

Instead of compiling a file to generate a byte code file which then has to be loaded,  a
program may be executed interpretively by ``consulting'' the corresponding source file:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- consult(SourceFile [, OptionList ] ).
@r{or}
    | ?- consult(SourceFile, OptionList, PredList).
@end example

where @code{SourceFile} is a Prolog atom which is the name of a file containing a Prolog source
program;  @code{OptionList}  is  a  list of options to @bb{consult}; and @code{PredList} is a list of terms
P/N, where P is a predicate name and N its arity, specifying which predicates have  been
consulted  from  @code{SourceFile}; its principal use is for setting trace points on the predicates
in the file (@pxref{Debugging}).  Notice that @code{PredList} can only appear in @b{consult}/3.@REFILL

At this point, the options recognized for consult are the following:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @t{t} ``trace''
Causes a trace point to be set on any predicate  in  the  current  file
that does not already have a trace point set.@REFILL

@item @t{v} ``verbose''
Causes information regarding which predicates have been consulted  to
be printed out. Default: off.@REFILL
@end table

In addition to the above, options for the macro expander are also recognized
(@pxref{Macros}).@REFILL

@bb{consult} will create an index on the printipal functor  of  the  first  argument  of  the
predicates being consulted, unless this is changed using the @b{index}/3 directive.  In particular,
note that if no index is desired on a predicate @t{foo}/n, then the directive @REFILL

@CENTER @t{:- index(foo, n, 0).}

@noindent
should be given.

It is important to note that SB-Prolog's @bb{consult} predicate is similar  to  that  of
Quintus  Prolog,  and behaves like C-Prolog's @bb{reconsult}.  This means that if a predicate
is defined across two or more files, consulting them will result in only the clauses  in
the file consulted last being used.@REFILL

@node Execution Directives, , Executing Programs, Getting Started
@section Execution Directives

Execution directives may be specified to @bb{compile} and @bb{consult} through :-/1.  If,  in  the
read  phase  of  @bb{compile} or @bb{consult}, a term with principal functor :-/1 is read in, this
term is executed directly via @b{call}/1.  This enables the user to dynamically  modify  the
environment, e.g. via @bb{op} declarations (@pxref{Operators}), asserts etc.@REFILL

A point to note is that if the environment is modified as a result of an  execution
directive, the modifications are visible only in that environment.  This means that consulted
code, which runs in the environment in which the source program is read  in  (and
which  is  modified  by  such  execution  directives) feel the effects of such execution
directives.  However, byte code resulting from compilation, which, in general,  executes
in an environment different from that in which the source was compiled, does not inherit
the effects of such directives.  Thus, an @bb{op} declaration can be used in a source file to
change  the  syntax and allow the remainder of the program to be parsed according to the
modified syntax; however, these modifications will not, in general, manifest  themselves
if  the  byte  code  is executed in another environment.  Of course, if the byte code is
loaded into the same environment as that in which the source program was compiled,  e.g.
through @REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile(foo, bar), load(bar).
@end example

@noindent
the effects of execution directives will continue to be felt.

@node Syntax, Operational Semantics, Getting Started, Top
@chapter Syntax

@menu
* Terms::	Syntax of SB-Prolog terms.
* Operators::   Defining operators (prefix, infix, postfix).
@end menu

@node Terms, Operators, , Syntax
@section Terms

The syntax of SB-Prolog is by and large compatible with that of C-Prolog.  The data
objects of the language are called terms.  A term is either a constant, a variable or a
compound term.  Constants can be integers or atoms.  The symbol for an atom must begin
with a lower case letter or the dollar sign @kbd{$}, and consist of any number of
letters, digits, underscores and dollar signs; if it contains any character other than
these, it must be enclosed within single quotes (Users are advised against using symbols
beginning with @kbd{$} or @kbd{_$}, however, in order to minimize the possibility of
conflicts with symbols internal to the system). As in other programming languages,
constants are definite elementary objects.@REFILL

Variables are distinguished by an initial capital letter or by the initial character
@kbd{_}, for example @REFILL

@CENTER @t{X@SP{3}Value@SP{3}A@SP{3}A1@SP{3}_3@SP{3}_RESULT@SP{3}_result}

If a variable is only referred to once, it does not need to   be   named  and   may   be
written as an anonymous variable, indicated by the underline character `@kbd{_}'.@REFILL

A variable should be thought of as  standing  for  some  definite  but unidentified
object.   A variable  is  not  simply  a  writeable storage  location  as  in  most
programming languages;  rather it is a local name for some data object, cf.   the  variable
of  pure  LISP  and constant declarations in Pascal.@REFILL

The structured data objects of the language are the  compound  terms.   A  compound
term  comprises  a  functor (called the principal functor of the term) and a sequence of
one or more terms called arguments.  A functor is characterised by its name, which is an
atom, and its arity or number of arguments.  For example the compound term whose functor
is named @code{point} of arity 3, with arguments @code{X}, @code{Y} and @code{Z}, is written:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{point(X,Y,Z)}

An atom is considered to be a functor of arity 0.

A functor or predicate symbol is uniquely identified by  its  name  and  arity  (in
other  words, it is possible for different symbols having different arities to share the
same name).  A functor or predicate symbol @code{p} with arity n is usually written @t{p}/n.@REFILL

One  may  think  of  a  functor  as  a record type and the arguments of a  compound
term  as  the   fields   of  a  record.   Compound terms are usefully pictured as trees.
For example, the term:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{s(np(john),vp(v(likes),np(mary)))}

@noindent
would be pictured as the structure

@example
                               s
                             /   \
                           np     vp
                           |     /  \
                        john    v    np
                                |    |
                             likes  mary
@end example

Sometimes it is convenient to write certain functors as operators -- 2-ary functors
may  be  declared  as infix operators and 1-ary functors as prefix or postfix operators.
Thus it is possible to write:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{X+Y@SP{3}(P;Q)@SP{3}(X<Y)@SP{3}+X@SP{3}P;}

@noindent
as optional alternatives to

@CENTER @t{+(X,Y)@SP{3};(P,Q)@SP{3}<(X,Y)@SP{3}+(X)@SP{3};(P)}

Operators are described fully in the next section.

Lists form an important class of data structures in Prolog.  They  are  essentially
the  same  as  the  lists  of LISP: a list either is the atom @t{[]}, representing the empty
list, or is a compound term  with   functor   `.'/2  and   two   arguments   which   are
respectively  the  head  and  tail  of  the  list.  Thus  a  list  of  the  first  three
natural  numbers  is  the structure:@REFILL

@example
                              .
                             / \
                            1   .
                               / \
                              2   .
                                 / \
                                3   []
@end example

@noindent
which could be written, using the standard syntax, as @t{.(1,.(2,.(3,[])))},  but  which  is
normally  written, in a special list notation, as @t{[1,2,3]}.  The special list notation in
the case when the tail of  a  list  is  a variable is exemplified by:@REFILL

@example
                    [X|L]            [a,b|L]
@r{representing}
                       .                .
                      / \              / \
                     X   L            a   .
                                         / \
                                        b   L
@end example

@noindent
respectively.

Note that this list syntax is only syntactic sugar for terms of the form @t{`.'(_,  _)}
and does not provide any new facilities that were not available otherwise.@REFILL

For convenience, a  further   notational   variant   is   allowed   for  lists   of
integers  which correspond to ASCII character codes.  Lists written in this notation are
called strings.  For example,@REFILL

@CENTER @t{"Prolog"}

@noindent
represents exactly the same list as

@CENTER @t{[80,114,111,108,111,103]}

@node Operators, , Terms, Syntax
@section Operators

Operators in Prolog are simply a notational convenience.  For example, the expression @REFILL

@CENTER @t{2 + 1}

@noindent
could also be written @t{+(2,1)}.  It should be noticed that this expression represents  the
structure @REFILL

@example
                                 +
                               /   \
                              2     1
@end example

@noindent
and not the number 3.  The addition would only be performed if the structure was  passed
as an argument to an appropriate procedure (such as @b{eval}/2, @pxref{Arithmetic}).@REFILL

The Prolog syntax caters for operators of three main kinds -- infix, prefix and postfix.
An infix operator appears between its two arguments, while a prefix operator precedes its
single argument and a postfix operator is written after its single argument.@REFILL

Each operator has a precedence, which is a number from 1 to 1200.  The precedence is used
to disambiguate expressions where the structure of the term denoted is not made explicit
through parenthesization.  The general rule is that the operator with the highest
precedence is the principal functor.  Thus if @samp{+} has a higher precedence than
@samp{/}, then @samp{a+b/c} and @samp{a+(b/c)} are equivalent and denote the term
@code{+(a,/(b,c))}.  Note that the infix form of the term @code{/(+(a,b),c)} must be
written with explicit parentheses, @samp{(a+b)/c}.@REFILL

If there are two operators in the subexpression having the same highest precedence, the
ambiguity must be resolved from the types of the operators.  The possible
types for an infix operator are:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{xfx@SP{3}xfy@SP{3}yfx}

With an operator of type @code{xfx}, it is a requirement that both of the two
subexpressions which are the arguments of the operator must be of lower precedence than
the operator itself, i.e.  their principal functors must be of lower precedence, unless
the subexpression is explicitly bracketed (which gives it zero precedence).  With an
operator of type @code{xfy}, only the first or left-hand subexpression must be of lower
precedence; the second can be of the same precedence as the main operator; and vice versa
for an operator of type @code{yfx}.@REFILL

For example, if the operators @code{+} and @code{-} both have type @code{yfx} and are of
the same precedence, then the expression @samp{a-b+c} is valid, and means @samp{(a-b)+c},
i.e.  @code{+(-(a,b),c)}.  Note that the expression would be invalid if the operators had
type @code{xfx}, and would mean @samp{a-(b+c)}, i.e. @code{-(a,+(b,c))}, if the types were
both @code{xfy}.@REFILL

The possible types for a prefix operator are

@CENTER @t{fx@SP{3}fy}

@noindent
and for a postfix operator they are

@CENTER @t{xf@SP{3}yf}

The meaning of the types should be clear by  analogy  with  those  for infix
operators.@REFILL

As an example, if @bb{not} were declared as a prefix operator of type @code{fy}, then
`@b{not not @t{P}}' would be a permissible way to write `@t{@b{not}(@b{not}(P))}. If the
type were @code{fx}, the preceding expression would not be legal, although `@t{@b{not} P}'
would still be a permissible form for `@t{@b{not}(P)}'.@REFILL

In SB-Prolog, a functor named @code{name} is declared as an operator of type @code{type}
and precedence @code{precedence} by calling the evaluable predicate @bb{op}:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- op(precedence, type, name).
@end example

The argument @code{name} can also be a list of names of operators of the same @code{type}
and @code{precedence}.@REFILL

It is possible to have more than one operator of the  same  name, so long  as  they
are  of different kinds, i.e.  infix, prefix or postfix.  An operator of any kind may be
redefined by a new declaration  of  the same  kind.   This  applies equally to operators
which are provided as standard in SB-Prolog, namely:@REFILL

@example
          :- op(  1200,   xfx,    [ :-, --> ]).
          :- op(  1200,   fx,     [ :- ]).
          :- op(  1198,   xfx,    [ ::- ]).
          :- op( 1150,    fy,     [ mode, public, dynamic ]).
          :- op(  1100,   xfy,    [ ; ]).
          :- op(  1050,   xfy,    [ -> ]).
          :- op(  1000,   xfy,    [ ',' ]).
          :- op(  900,    fy,     [ not, \+, spy, nospy ]).
          :- op(  700,    xfx,    [ =, is, =.., ==, \==, @@<, @@>, @@=<, @@>=,
                                    =:=, =\=, <, >, =<, >=, ?=, \= ]).
          :- op(  661,    xfy,    [ `.' ]).
          :- op(  500,    yfx,    [ +, -, /\, \/ ]).
          :- op(  500,    fx,     [ +, - ]).
          :- op(  400,    yfx,    [ *, /, //, <<, >> ]).
          :- op(  300,    xfx,    [ mod ]).
          :- op(  200,    xfy,    [ ^ ]).
@end example

Operator declarations are most usefully placed in directives at  the  top  of  your
program  files.  In  this case the directive should be a command as shown above. Another
common method of organisation is to have one file just containing  commands  to  declare
all the necessary operators. This file is then always consulted first.@REFILL

Note that a comma written literally as  a  punctuation  character can  be  used  as
though it were an infix operator of precedence 1000 and type code{xfy}:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{X,Y@SP{3}','(X,Y)}

@noindent
represent the same compound term.  But note that a comma written as  a  quoted  atom  is
not a standard operator.@REFILL

Note also that the arguments of a compound term written in standard syntax must be
expressions of precedence below 1000. Thus it is necessary to parenthesize the expression
@code{P :- Q} in:@REFILL

@CENTER @code{assert((P :- Q))}

The following syntax restrictions serve  to remove potential ambiguity  associated  with
prefix operators.@REFILL

In a term written in standard syntax, the  principal  functor  and  its   following
@t{(}  must  not be separated by any whitespace.  Thus:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{point (X,Y,Z)}

@noindent
is invalid syntax (unless @code{point} were declared as a prefix operator).

If the argument of a prefix operator  starts  with  a  @kbd{(},   this @kbd{(} must be
separated   from   the  operator  by  at  least  one  space  or other non-printable
character.  Thus:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{:-(p;q),r.}

@noindent
(where @code{:-} is the prefix operator) is invalid syntax, and must be written as:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{:- (p;q),r.}

If a prefix  operator  is  written  without  an  argument,  as  an ordinary   atom,
the   atom   is   treated   as   an expression of the same precedence as the prefix
operator, and  must  therefore  be  bracketed where necessary.  Thus  the  brackets
are necessary in @code{X = (?-)}.@REFILL

@node Operational Semantics, Evaluable Predicates, Syntax, Top
@chapter SB-Prolog: Operational Semantics

@menu
* Standard Execution Behaviour::
* Cuts and If-Then-Else::
* Unification of Floating Point Numbers::
@end menu

@node Standard Execution Behaviour, Cuts and If-Then-Else, , Operational Semantics
@section Standard Execution Behaviour

The normal execution behaviour of SB-Prolog follows the usual left to right order of
literals within a clause, and the textual top to bottom order of clauses for a predicate.
This corresponds to a depth first search of the leftmost SLD-tree for the program and the
given query.  Unification without occurs check is used, and execution backtracks to the
most recent choice point when unification fails.@REFILL

@node Cuts and If-Then-Else, Unification of Floating Point Numbers, Standard Execution Behaviour, Operational Semantics
@section Cuts and If-Then-Else

This standard execution behaviour of SB-Prolog can be changed using constructs like
@code{cut} (@samp{!}) and @code{if-then-else} (@samp{->}).  In SB-Prolog, cuts are usually
treated as hard, i.e.  discard choice points of all the literals to the left of the cut
in the clause containing the cut being executed, and also the choice point for the
parent predicate, i.e.
any remaining clauses for the predicate containing the cut being  executed.   There  are
some  situations,  however,  where  the  scope of a cut is restricted to be smaller than
this.  Restrictions apply under the following conditions:@REFILL

@enumerate
@item
The cut occurs in a term which has been constructed at runtime and  called  through
@b{call}/1, e.g. in:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{@dots{}, X = (p(Y), !, q(Y)), @dots{}, call(X), @dots{}}

In this case, the scope of the cut is restricted to be within the call, unless  one
of the following cases also apply and serve to restrict its scope further.@REFILL

@item
The cut occurs in a negated goal, or within the scope of the test of an
@code{if-then-else} (in an @code{if-then-else} of the form ``Test -> TruePart ;
FalsePart'', the test is the goal Test).  In these cases, the scope of the cut is
restricted to be within the negation or the test of the @code{if-then-else},
respectively.@REFILL
@end enumerate

In cases involving nested occurrences of these situations, the scope of the cut is
restricted  to that for the deepest such nested construct, i.e. most restricted.  For
example, in the construct:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{@dots{}, not((p(X) -> not((q(X), (r(X) -> s(X) ; (t(X), !, u(X))))))), @dots{}}

@noindent
the scope of the cut is restricted to the inner negation, and does not affect any choice
point that may have been set up for @code{p(X)}.@REFILL

@node Unification of Floating Point Numbers, , Cuts and If-Then-Else, Operational Semantics
@section Unification of Floating Point Numbers

As far as unification is concerned, no type distinction is  made  between  integers  and
floating  point  numbers,  and no explicit type conversion is necessary when unifying an
integer with a float.  However, due to the finite precision representation  of  floating
point  numbers and cumulative round-off errors in floating point arithmetic, comparisons
involving floating point numbers may not always give the expected results.  An effort is
made  to minimize surprises by considering two numbers x and y (at least one of which is
a float) to be unifiable if:@REFILL
@ifinfo

@center ||x| - |y||/min(|x|, |y|) < 10[-5]

@end ifinfo
@tex
$$||x|-|y||/\min(|x|,|y|) < 10^{-5}$$
@end tex

However, this  does  not guarantee immunity against round-off errors.  For the same reason, users
are warned that indexing on predicate arguments may  not  give  the
expected results if floating point numbers are involved.@REFILL

@node Evaluable Predicates, Debugging, Operational Semantics, Top
@chapter Evaluable Predicates

@menu
* Input and Output::
* Arithmetic::
* Convenience::
* Extra Control::
* Meta-Logical::
* Sets::
* Comparison of Terms::
* Buffers::
* Modification of the Program::
* Internal Database::
* State of the Program::
* Environmental::
* Global Values::
* Exotica::
@end menu

This section describes (most of) the evaluable predicates provided by SB-Prolog.   These
can  be  divided  into  three classes: inline predicates, builtin predicates and library
predicates.@REFILL

Inline predicates represent ``primitive'' operations in the WAM.  Calls  to  inline
predicates  are compiled into a sequence of WAM instructions in-line, i.e. without
actually making a call to the predicate.  Thus, for  example,  relational  predicates
(@t{>}/2, @t{>=}/2,  etc.)  compile  to,  essentially, a subtraction and a conditional branch.  Inline
predicates cannot be redefined by the user.  The table below lists the SB-Prolog  inline  predicates:@REFILL

@ifinfo
@example
        arg/3         =/2       </2    =</2
         >=/2         >/2      /\/2    \//2
         <</2        >>/2     =:=/2   =\=/2
         is/2        ?=/2      \=/2     \/1
  _$builtin/1    _$call/1  nonvar/1   var/1
    integer/1      real/1    halt/0  true/0
       fail/0
@end example
@end ifinfo
@iftex
@begingroup
@catcode`@&=4
@catcode`@#=6
@noindent
@centerline{@vbox{@halign{@hfil@tt#@quad&@hfil@tt#@quad&@hfil@tt#@quad&@hfil@tt#@cr
arg{@rm/3} & ={@rm/2} & <{@rm/2} & =<{@rm/2}@cr
>={@rm/2} & >{@rm/2} & /\{@rm/2} & \/{@rm/2}@cr
<<{@rm/2} & >>{@rm/2} & =:={@rm/2} & =\={@rm/2}@cr
is{@rm/2} & ?={@rm/2} & \={@rm/2} & \/{@rm/1}@cr
_$builtin{@rm/1} & _$call{@rm/1} & nonvar{@rm/1} & var{@rm/1}@cr
integer{@rm/1} & real{@rm/1} & halt{@rm/0} & true{@rm/0}@cr
fail{@rm/0}&&&@cr}}}
@endgroup
@end iftex

Unlike inline predicates, builtin predicates are implemented by C functions in  the
simulator,  and  accessed  via  the  inline predicate @bb{_$builtin}/1.  Thus, if a builtin
predicate @t{foo}/3 was defined as builtin number 38, there would be  a  definition  in  the
system of the form:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{foo(X,Y,Z) :- '_$builtin'(38).}

In effect, a builtin is simply a segment of code in a large case (i.e.  switch)
statement.  Each builtin is identified internally by an integer, referred to as its
``builtin number'', associated with it.  The code for a builtin with builtin number k
k[th.]  case in the switch statement.  SB-Prolog limits the total number of builtins to
256.@REFILL

Builtins, unlike inline predicates,  can be redefined by the  user.   For  example,
the predicate @t{foo}/3 above can be redefined simply by compiling the new definition into a
directory such that during dynamic loading, the  new  definition  would  be  encountered
first and loaded.@REFILL

For a list of the builtins currently provided: @pxref{Index of Evaluable Predicates}.
@xref{Adding Builtins} for a description of the procedure to be followed in order to
define new builtin predicates.@REFILL

Like builtin predicates, library predicates may also be redefined by the user.  The
essential  difference  between builtin and library predicates is that whereas the former
are coded into the simulator in C, the latter are written in Prolog.@REFILL

@node Input and Output, Arithmetic, , Evaluable Predicates
@section Input and Output

Input and output are done with respect to the current input and output streams.  These can
be set, reset or checked using the file handling predicates described below.  The default
input and output streams are denoted by @code{user}, and refer to the user's
terminal.@REFILL

@menu
* File Handling::
* Term I/O::
* Character I/O::
@end menu

@node File Handling, Term I/O, , Input and Output
@subsection File Handling

@table @asis
@item @b{see}(F)
F becomes the current input stream.  F must be instantiated to an atom at the time of the
call.@REFILL

@item @b{seeing}(F)
F is unified with the name of the current input file.@REFILL

@item @b{seen}
Closes the current input stream.@REFILL

@item @b{tell}(F)
F becomes the current output stream.  F must be instantiated to an atom at the time of the
call.@REFILL

@item @b{telling}(F)
F is unified with the name of the current output file.@REFILL

@item @b{told}
Closes the current output stream.@REFILL

@item @b{$exists}(F)
Succeeds if file F exists.@REFILL
@end table

@node Term I/O, Character I/O, File Handling, Input and Output
@subsection Term I/O

@table @asis
@item @b{read}(X)
The next term, delimited by a full stop (i.e.  a ``.'' followed by a carriage-return or a
space), is read from the current input stream and unified with X. The syntax of the term
must accord with current operator declarations.  If a call @b{read}(X) causes the end of
the current input stream to be reached, X is unified with the atom @samp{end_of_file}.
Further calls to read for the same stream will then cause an error failure.@REFILL

@item @b{write}(X)
The term X is written to the current output stream according to operator declarations in
force.@REFILL

@item @b{display}(X)
The term X is displayed on the terminal.@REFILL

@item @b{writeq}(Term)
Similar to @b{write}(Term), but the names of atoms and functors are quoted where necessary
to make the result acceptable as input to read.@REFILL

@item @b{print}(Term)
Prints out the term Term onto the current output stream.  This predicate provides a handle
for user-defined pretty-printing.  If Term is a variable then it is written using
@b{write}/1; otherwise, if a user-defined predicate @b{portray}/1 is defined, then a call
is made to @b{portray}(Term); otherwise, @b{print}/1 is equivalent to @b{write}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{writename}(Term)
If Term is an uninstantiated variable, its name, which looks a lot like an address in
memory, is written out; otherwise, the principal functor of Term is written out.@REFILL

@item @b{writeqname}(Term)
As for @b{writename}, but the names are quoted where necessary.@REFILL

@item @b{print_al}(N, A)
Prints A (which must be an atom or a number) left-aligned in a field of width N, with
blanks padded to the right.  If A's print name is longer than the field width N, then A is
printed but with no right padding.@REFILL

@item @b{print_ar}(N, A)
Prints A (which must be an atom or a number) right-aligned in a field of width N, with
blanks padded to the left.  If A's print name is longer than the field width N, then A is
printed but with no left padding.@REFILL

@item @b{portray_term}(Term)
Writes out the term Term on the current output stream.  Variables are treated specially:
an uninstantiated variable is printed out as Vn, where n is a number.@REFILL

@item @b{portray_clause}(Term)
Writes out the term Term, interpreted as a clause, on the current output stream.
Variables are treated as in @b{portray_term}/1.@REFILL
@end table

@node Character I/O, , Term I/O, Input and Output
@subsection Character I/O

@table @asis
@item @b{nl}
A new line is started on the current output stream.@REFILL

@item @b{get0}(N)
N is the ASCII code of the next character from the current input stream.  If the current
input stream reaches its end of file, a -1 is returned (however, unlike in C-Prolog, the
input stream is not closed on encountering end-of-file).@REFILL

@item @b{get}(N)
N is the ASCII code of the next non-blank printable character from the current input
stream. It has the same behaviour as @b{get0} on end of file.@REFILL

@item @b{put}(N)
ASCII character code N is output to the current output stream.  N must be an integer.@REFILL

@item @b{tab}(N)
N spaces are output to the current output stream.  N must be an integer.@REFILL
@end table

@node Arithmetic, Convenience, Input and Output, Evaluable Predicates
@section Arithmetic

Arithmetic is performed by evaluable predicates which take as arguments arithmetic
expressions and evaluate them.  An arithmetic expression is a term built from evaluable
functors, numbers and variables.  At the time of evaluation, each variable in an
arithmetic expression must be bound to a number or to an arithmetic expression.  Each
evaluable functor stands for an arithmetic operation.@REFILL

The evaluable functors are as follows, where X and Y are arithmetic expressions.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item X + Y
addition.

@item X - Y
subtraction.

@item X * Y
multiplication.

@item X / Y
division.

@item X // Y
integer division.

@item X @b{mod} Y
X (integer) modulo Y.

@item -X
unary minus.

@item X /\ Y
integer bitwise conjunction.

@item X \/ Y
integer bitwise disjunction.

@item X << Y
integer bitwise left shift of X by Y places.

@item X >> Y
integer bitwise right shift of X by Y places.

@item \X
integer bitwise negation.
@end table

As far as unification is concerned, no type distinction is made between integers and
floating point numbers, and no explicit type conversion is necessary when unifying an
integer with a float.  However, due to the finite precision representation of floating
point numbers and cumulative round-off errors in floating point arithmetic, comparisons
involving floating point numbers may not always give the expected results.  An effort is
made to minimize surprises by considering two numbers x and y (at least one of which is a
float) to be unifiable if:@REFILL

@tex
$$||x| - |y||/\min(|x|, |y|) < 10^{-5}$$
@end tex
@ifinfo
@center ||x| - |y||/min(|x|, |y|) < 10[-5]
@end ifinfo

The user should note, however, that this does not guarantee immunity against round-off
errors.@REFILL

The arithmetic evaluable predicates are as follows, where X and Y stand for arithmetic
expressions, and Z for some term.  Note that this means that is only evaluates one of
its arguments as an arithmetic expression (the right-hand side one), whereas all the
comparison predicates evaluate both their arguments.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item Z @b{is} X
Arithmetic expression X is evaluated and the result, is unified with Z. Fails if X is not
an arithmetic expression.  Unlike many other Prolog systems, variables in the expression X
may be bound to other arithmetic expressions as well as to numbers.@REFILL

@item @b{eval}(E, X)
Evaluates the arithmetic expression E and unifies the result with the term X.  Fails if E
is not an arithmetic expression. (Thus, @b{eval}/2 is, except for the switched argument
order, the same as @b{is}/2.  It's around mainly for historical reasons.)@REFILL

@item X =:= Y
The values of X and Y are equal.  If either X or Y involve compound subexpressions that
are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using @b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item X =\= Y
The values of X and Y are not equal.  If either X or Y involve compound subexpressions
that are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using @b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item X < Y
The value of X is less than the value of Y.  If either X or Y involve compound
subexpressions that are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using
@b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item X > Y
The value of X is greater than the value of Y.  If either X or Y involve compound
subexpressions that are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using
@b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item X =< Y
The value of X is less than or equal to the value of Y.  If either X or Y involve compound
subexpressions that are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using
@b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item X >= Y
The value of X is greater than or equal to the value of Y.  If either X or Y involve
compound subexpressions that are created at runtime, they should first be evaluated using
@b{eval}/2.@REFILL

@item @b{floor}(X, Y)
If X is a floating point number in the call and Y is free, then Y is instantiated to the
largest integer whose absolute value is not greater than the absolute value of X; if X is
uninstantiated in the call and Y is an integer, then X is instantiated to the smallest
float not less than Y.@REFILL

@item @b{floatc}(F, M, E)
If F is a number while M and E are uninstantiated in the call, then M is instantiated to
a float m (of magnitude less than 1), and E to an integer n, such that @REFILL
@tex
$${\rm F} = {\rm m}\times 2^{\rm\scriptstyle n}$$
@end tex
@ifinfo

@center F = m * 2[n].

@end ifinfo
If F is uninstantiated in the call while M is a float and E an integer, then F becomes
instantiated to
@tex
$M\times 2^{\rm\scriptstyle E}$.
@end tex
@ifinfo
M * 2[E].@REFILL
@end ifinfo

@item @b{exp}(X, Y)
If X is instantiated to a number and Y is uninstantiated in the call, then Y is
instantiated to
@tex
$\exp({\rm X})$
@end tex
@ifinfo
e[X]
@end ifinfo
(where  e = 2.71828...); if X is uninstantiated in the call
while Y is instantiated to a positive number, then X is instantiated to
@tex
$\log({\rm Y})$.
@end tex
@ifinfo
log<e>(Y).@REFILL
@end ifinfo

@item @b{square}(X, Y)
If X is instantiated to a number while Y is uninstantiated in the call, then Y becomes
instantiated to
@tex
${\rm X}^2$;
@end tex
@ifinfo
X[2];
@end ifinfo
if X is uninstantiated in the call while Y is instantiated to a positive number, then X
becomes instantiated to the positive square root of Y (if Y is negative in the call, X
becomes instantiated to 0.0).@REFILL

@item @b{sin}(X, Y)
If X is instantiated to a number (representing an angle in radians) and Y is
uninstantiated in the call, then Y becomes instantiated to
@tex
$\sin({\rm X})$
@end tex
@ifinfo
sin(X)
@end ifinfo
(the user should check the magnitude of X to make sure that the result is meaningful).
If Y is instantiated to a number between
@tex
$-\pi/2$ and $\pi/2$
@end tex
@ifinfo
-pi/2 and pi/2
@end ifinfo
and X is uninstantiated in the call, then X becomes instantiated to
@tex
$\arcsin({\rm Y})$.
@end tex
@ifinfo
sin[-1](Y).@REFILL
@end ifinfo
@end table

@node Convenience, Extra Control, Arithmetic, Evaluable Predicates
@section Convenience

@table @asis
@item P , Q
P and then Q.

@item P ; Q
P or Q.

@item @b{true}
Always  succeeds.

@item X = Y
Defined as if by the clause Z=Z, i.e. X and Y are unified.

@item X \= Y
Succeeds if X and Y are not unifiable, fails if X and Y are unifiable.  It is thus
equivalent to @b{not}(X = Y), but is significantly more efficient.@REFILL

@item X ?= Y
Succeeds if X and Y are unifiable and fails if they are not, but does not instantiate any
variables.  Thus, it tests whether X and Y are unifiable.  Equivalent to, but
significantly more efficient than:@REFILL

@CENTER @b{not}(@b{not}(X = Y))
@end table

@node Extra Control, Meta-Logical, Convenience, Evaluable Predicates
@section Extra Control

@table @asis
@item !
Cut (discard) all choice points made since the parent goal started execution.  (The scope
of cut in different contexts is discussed in @xref{Cuts and If-Then-Else}).@REFILL

@item @b{not} P
If the goal P has a solution, fail, otherwise succeed.  It is defined as if
by @REFILL
@example
                   not(P) :- P, !, fail.
                   not(_).
@end example

@item P -> Q ; R
Analogous to ``if P then Q else R'' i.e.  defined as if by @REFILL

@example
                   P -> Q ; R :- P, !, Q.
                   P -> Q ; R :- R.
@end example

@item P -> Q
When occurring other than as one of the alternatives of a disjunction, is equivalent
to @REFILL

@example
                   P -> Q ; fail.
@end example

@item @b{repeat}
Generates an infinite sequence of backtracking choices.  It is defined by the
clauses:@REFILL

@example
                   repeat.
                   repeat :- repeat.
@end example

@item @b{fail}
Always fails.
@end table

@node Meta-Logical, Sets, Extra Control, Evaluable Predicates
@section Meta-Logical

@table @asis
@item @b{var}(X)
Tests whether X is currently instantiated to a variable.

@item @b{nonvar}(X)
Tests whether X is currently instantiated to a non-variable term.@REFILL

@item @b{atom}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to an atom (i.e.  a non-variable term of arity 0,
other than a number).@REFILL

@item @b{integer}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to an integer.@REFILL

@item @b{real}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to a floating point number.@REFILL

@item @b{float}(X)
Same as @b{real}/1, checks that X is currently instantiated to a floating point
number.@REFILL

@item @b{number}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to a number, i.e.  that it is either an integer or
a real.@REFILL

@item @b{atomic}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to an atom or number.@REFILL

@item @b{structure}(X)
Checks that X is currently instantiated to a compound term, i.e. to a nonvariable term
that is not atomic.@REFILL

@item @b{is_buffer}(X)
Succeeds if X is instantiated to a buffer.@REFILL

@item @b{functor}(T, F, N)
The principal functor of term T has name F and arity N, where F is either an atom or,
provided N is 0, a number. Initially, either T must be instantiated to a non-variable, or
F and N must be instantiated to, respectively, either an atom and a non-negative integer
or an integer and 0. If these conditions are not satisfied, an error message is given.  In
the case where T is initially instantiated to a variable, the result of the call is to
instantiate T to the most general term having the principal functor
indicated.@REFILL

@item @b{arg}(I, T, X)
Initially, I must be instantiated to a positive integer and T to a compound term.  The
result of the call is to unify X with the Ith argument of term T.  (The arguments are
numbered from 1 upwards.) If the initial conditions are not satisfied or I is out of
range, the call merely fails.@REFILL

@item X =.. Y
Y is a list whose head is the atom corresponding to the principal functor of X and whose
tail is the argument list of that functor in X. E.g.@REFILL

@example
               product(0,N,N-1) =.. [product,0,N,N-1]

               N-1 =.. [-,N,1]

               product =.. [product]
@end example

If X is instantiated to a variable, then Y must be instantiated either to a list of
determinate length whose head is an atom, or to a list of length 1 whose head is a
number.@REFILL

@item @b{name}(X,L)
If X is an atom or a number then L is a list of the ASCII codes of the characters
comprising the name of X. E.g.@REFILL

@example
               name(product,[112,114,111,100,117,99,116])
@end example

i.e.  @b{name}(product,"product").

If X is instantiated to a variable, L must be instantiated to a list of ASCII character
codes.  E.g.@REFILL

@example
              | ?- name(X,[104,101,108,108,111])).
              X = hello

              | ?- name(X,"hello").
              X = hello
@end example

@item @b{call}(X)
If X is a nonvariable term in the program text, then it is executed exactly as if X
appeared in the program text instead of call(X), e.g.@REFILL

@example
              @dots{}, p(a), call( (q(X), r(Y)) ), s(X), @dots{}
@end example

@noindent
is equivalent to

@example
              @dots{}, p(a), q(X), r(Y), s(X), @dots{}
@end example

However, if X is a variable in the program text, then if at runtime X is instantiated to a
term which would be acceptable as the body of a clause, the goal @b{call}(X) is executed
as if that term appeared textually in place of the @b{call}(X), except that any cut (@samp{!})
occurring in X will remove only those choice points in X.  If X is not instantiated as
described above, an error message is printed and call fails.@REFILL

@item X
(where X is a variable) Exactly the same as @b{call}(X).  However, we prefer the explicit
usage of @b{call}/1 as good programming practice, and the use of a top level variable
subgoal elicits a warning from the compiler.@REFILL

@item @b{conlength}(C, L)
Succeeds if the length of the print name of the constant C (which can be an atom, buffer
or integer), in bytes, is L.  If C is a buffer (@pxref{Buffers}), it is the length of the
buffer; if C is an integer, it is the length of the decimal representation of that
integer, i.e., the number of bytes that a @b{$writename} will use.@REFILL
@end table

@node Sets, Comparison of Terms, Meta-Logical, Evaluable Predicates
@section Sets

When there are many solutions to a problem, and when all those solutions are required to
be collected together, this can be achieved by repeatedly backtracking and gradually
building up a list of the solutions.  The following evaluable predicates are provided to
automate this process.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{setof}(X, P, S)
Read this as ``S is the set of all instances of X such that P is provable''.  If P is not
provable, @b{setof}(X,P,S) succeeds with S instantiated to the empty list @t{[]}.  The term P
specifies a goal or goals as in @b{call}(P). S is a set of terms represented as a list of
those terms, without duplicates, in the standard order for terms (@pxref{Comparison of
Terms}). If there are uninstantiated variables in P which do not also appear in X, then a
call to this evaluable predicate may backtrack, generating alternative values for S
corresponding to different instantiations of the free variables of P.  Variables occurring
in P will not be treated as free if they are explicitly bound within P by an existential
quantifier.  An existential quantification is written:@REFILL

@CENTER Y^Q

@noindent
meaning ``there exists a Y such that Q is true'', where Y is some Prolog term (usually, a
variable, or tuple or list of variables).@REFILL

@item @b{bagof}(X, P, Bag)
This is the same as @b{setof} except that the list (or alternative lists) returned will
not be ordered, and may contain duplicates.  If P is unsatisfiable, @b{bagof} succeeds
binding Bag to the empty list.  The effect of this relaxation is to save considerable time
and space in execution.@REFILL

@item @b{findall}(X, P, L)
Similar to @b{bagof}/3, except that variables in P that do not occur in X are treated as
local, and alternative lists are not returned for different bindings of such variables.
The list L is, in general, unordered, and may contain duplicates.  If P is unsatisfiable,
@b{findall} succeeds binding S to the empty list.@REFILL

@item X^P
The system recognises this as meaning ``there exists an X such that P is true'', and
treats it as equivalent to @b{call}(P).  The use of this explicit existential quantifier
outside the @b{setof} and @b{bagof} constructs is superfluous.@REFILL
@end table

@node Comparison of Terms, Buffers, Sets, Evaluable Predicates
@section Comparison of Terms

These evaluable predicates are meta-logical.  They treat uninstantiated variables as
objects with values which may be compared, and they never instantiate those variables.
They should not be used when what you really want is arithmetic comparison
(@xref{Arithmetic}) or unification.  The predicates make reference to a standard total
ordering of terms, which is as follows:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item variables
in a standard order (roughly, oldest first -- the order is not related to the names of
variables);@REFILL

@item numbers
@tex
from $-\infty$ to $+\infty$;
@end tex
@ifinfo
from -infinity to +infinity;@REFILL
@end ifinfo

@item atoms
in alphabetical (i.e. ASCII) order;

@item complex terms
ordered first by arity, then by the name of principal functor, then by the arguments (in
left-to-right order).@REFILL
@end table

For example, here is a list of terms in the standard order:

@CENTER @t{[ X, -9, 1, fie, foe, fum, X = Y, fie(0,2), fie(1,1) ]}

The basic predicates for comparison of arbitrary terms are:

@table @asis
@item X == Y
Tests if the terms currently instantiating X and Y are literally identical (in particular,
variables in equivalent positions in the two terms must be identical).  For example, the
question @REFILL

@example
    | ?- X == Y.
@end example

@noindent
fails (answers "no") because X and Y are distinct uninstantiated variables.  However, the
question @REFILL

@example
    | ?- X = Y, X == Y.
@end example

@noindent
succeeds because the first goal unifies the two variables
(@pxref{Convenience}).@REFILL

@item X \== Y
Tests if the terms currently instantiating X and Y are not literally
identical.@REFILL

@item T1 @@< T2
Term T1 is before term T2 in the standard order.

@item T1 @@> T2
Term T1 is after term T2 in the standard order.

@item T1 @@=< T2
Term T1 is not after term T2 in the standard order.

@item T1 @@>= T2
Term T1 is not before term T2 in the standard order.
@end table

Some further predicates involving comparison of terms are:

@table @asis
@item @b{compare}(Op, T1, T2)
The result of comparing terms T1 and T2 is Op, where the possible values for Op
are:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item =
if T1 is identical to T2,

@item <
if T1 is before T2 in the standard order,

@item >
if T1 is after T2 in the standard order.
@end table

Thus @b{compare}(=,T1,T2) is equivalent to T1 == T2.

@item @b{sort}(L1, L2)
The elements of the list L1 are sorted into the standard order, and any identical (i.e.
`==') elements are merged, yielding the list L2.@REFILL

@item @b{keysort}(L1, L2)
The list L1 must consist of items of the form Key-Value.  These items are sorted into
order according to the value of Key, yielding the list L2.  No merging takes
place.@REFILL
@end table

@node Buffers, Modification of the Program, Comparison of Terms, Evaluable Predicates
@section Buffers

SB-Prolog supports the concept of buffers.  A buffer is actually a constant and the
characters that make up the buffer is the name of the constant.  However, the symbol table
entry for a buffer is not hashed and thus is not added to the obj-list, so two different
buffers will never unify.  Buffers can be allocated either in permanent space or on the
heap.  Buffers in permanent space stay there forever; buffers on the heap are deallocated
when the ``allocate buffer'' goal is backtracked over.@REFILL

A buffer allocated on the heap can either be a simple buffer, or it can be allocated as a
subbuffer of another buffer already on the heap.  A subbuffer will be deallocated when its
superbuffer is deallocated.@REFILL

There are occasions when it is not known, in advance, exactly how much space will be
required and so how big a buffer should be allocated.  Sometimes this problem can be
overcome by allocating a large buffer and then, after using as much as is needed,
returning the rest of the buffer to the system. This can be done, but only under very
limited circumstances: a buffer is allocated from the end of the permanent space, the top
of the heap, or from the next available space in the superbuffer; if no more space has
been used beyond the end of the buffer, a tail portion of the buffer can be returned to
the system. This operation is called ``trimming'' the buffer.@REFILL

The following is a list of library predicates for buffer management:

@table @asis
@item @b{alloc_perm}(Size, Buff)
Allocates a buffer with a length Size in the permanent (i.e.  program) area.  Size must be
bound to a number. On successful return, Buff will be bound to the allocated buffer.  The
buffer, being in the permanent area, is never de-allocated.@REFILL

@item @b{alloc_heap}(Size, Buff)
Allocates a buffer of size Size on the heap and binds Buff to it. Since it is on the heap,
it will be deallocated on backtracking.@REFILL

@item @b{trimbuff}(Type, Buff, Newlen)
This allows (in some very restricted circumstances) the changing of the size of a buffer.
Type is 0 if the buffer is permanent, 1 if the buffer is on the heap. Buff is the buffer.
Newlen is an integer: the size (which should be smaller than the original length of the
buffer) to make the buffer. If the buffer is at the top of the heap (if heap buffer) or
the end of the program area (if permanent) then the heap-top (or program area top) will be
readjusted down.  The length of the buffer will be modified to Newlen.  This is
(obviously) a very low-level primitive and is for hackers only to implement grungy
stuff.@REFILL

@item @b{conlength}(Constant,Length)
Succeeds if the length of the print name of the constant Constant (which can be an atom,
buffer or integer), in bytes, is Length.  If Constant is a buffer, it is the length of the
buffer; if Constant is an integer, it is the length of the decimal representation of that
integer, i.e., the number of bytes that a @b{$writename} will use.@REFILL
@end table

@node Modification of the Program, Internal Database, Buffers, Evaluable Predicates
@section Modification of the Program

The predicates defined in this section allow modification of the program as it is actually
running.  Clauses can be added to the program (asserted) or removed from the program
(retracted).  At the lowest level, the system supports the asserting of clauses with upto
one literal in the body.  It does this by allocating a buffer and compiling code for the
clause into that buffer.  Such a buffer is called a ``clause reference'' (clref).  The
clref is then added to a chain of clrefs.  The chain of clrefs has a header, which is a
small buffer called a ``predicate reference'' (prref), which contains pointers to the
beginning and end of its chain of clrefs.  Clause references are quite similar to
``database references'' of C-Prolog, and can be called.@REFILL

When clauses are added to the program through @b{assert}, an index is normally created on
the principal functor of the first argument in the head of the clause.  The argument on
which the index is being created may be changed via the @b{index}/3 directive.  In
particular, if no index is desired on a predicate, this should be specified using the
@b{index}/3 directive with the argument number set to zero, e.g. if no index is desired on
a predicate @b{foo}/3, then the directive @REFILL

@CENTER @t{:- index(foo, 3, 0).}

@noindent
should be specified.

The predicates that can be used to modify the program are the following:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{assert}(C)
The current instance of C is interpreted as a clause and is added to the program (with new
private variables replacing any uninstantiated variables), at the end of the list of
clauses for that predicate.  C must be instantiated to a non-variable.@REFILL

@item @b{assert}(C, Ref)
As for @b{assert}/1, but also unifies Ref with the clause reference of the clause
asserted.@REFILL

@item @b{asserti}(C,N)
The current instance of C, interpreted as a clause, is asserted to the program with an
index on its N[th] argument.  If N is zero, no index is created.@REFILL

@item @b{asserta}(C)
Similar to @b{assert}(C), except that the new clause becomes the first clause of the procedure
concerned.@REFILL

@item @b{asserta}(C, Ref)
Similar to @b{asserta}(C), but also unifies Ref with the clause reference of the clause
asserted.@REFILL

@item @b{assertz}(C)
Similar to @b{assert}(C), except that the new clause becomes the last clause of the procedure
concerned.@REFILL

@item @b{assertz}(C, Ref)
Similar to @b{assertz}(C), but also unifies Ref with the clause reference of the clause
asserted.@REFILL

@item @b{assert_union}(P, Q)
The clauses for Q are added to the clauses for P.  For example, the call @REFILL

@example
    | ?- assert_union(p(X,Y),q(X,Y)).
@end example

@noindent
has the effect of adding the rule

@example
    p(X,Y) :- q(X,Y).
@end example

@noindent
as the last rule defining @t{p}/2.  If P is not defined, it results in the call to Q being
the only clause for P.@REFILL

The variables in the arguments to @b{assert_union/2} are not significant, e.g.  the above
would have been equivalent to @REFILL

@example
    | ?- assert_union(p(Y,X),q(X,Y)).
@r{or}
    | ?- assert_union(p(_,_),q(_,_)).
@end example

However, the arities of the two predicates involved must match, e.g.  even though the
goal:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- assert_union(p(X,Y), r(X,Y,Z)).
@end example

@noindent
will succeed, the predicate @t{p}/2 will not in any way depend on the clauses
for @t{r}/3.@REFILL

@item @b{assert}(Clause,AZ,Index,Clref)
Asserts a clause to a predicate.  Clause is the clause to assert.  AZ is 0 for insertion
as the first clause, 1 for insertion as the last clause.  Index is the number of the
argument on which to index (0 for no indexing).  Clref is returned as the clause reference
of the fact newly asserted.  If the main functor symbol of Clause has been declared (by
@b{$assertf_alloc_t}/2, see below) to have its clauses on the heap, the clref will be
allocated there. If the predicate symbol of Clause is undefined, it will be initialized
and Clause added. If the predicate symbol has compiled clauses, it is first converted to
be dynamic (cf{.} @b{symtype}/2, @pxref{Internal Database}) by adding a special clref that
calls the compiled clauses.  Fact, AZ and Index are input arguments, and should be
instantiated at the time of call; Clref is an output argument, and should be
uninstantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{clause}(P,Q)
P must be bound to a non-variable term, and the program is searched for a clause Cl whose
head matches P.  The head and body of the clause Cl is unified with P and Q respectively.
If Cl is a unit clause, Q will be unified with `true'.  Only interpreted clauses, i.e.
those created through assert, can be accessed via @b{clause}/2.@REFILL

@item @b{clause}(Head,Body,Ref)
Similar to @b{clause}(Head,Body) but also unifies Ref with the database reference of the
clause concerned.  @b{clause}/3 can be executed in one of two modes: either Head must be
instantiated to a non-variable term at the time of the call, or Ref must be instantiated
to a database reference.  As in the case of @b{clause}/2, only interpreted clauses, i.e.
those created through assert, can be accessed via @b{clause}/3.@REFILL

@item @b{retract}(Clause)
The first clause in the program that unifies with Clause is deleted from the program.
This predicate may be used in a non-deterministic fashion, i.e. it will successively
backtrack to retract clauses whose heads match Head.  Head must be initially instantiated
to a non-variable. In the current implementation, retract works only for asserted (e.g.
consulted) clauses.@REFILL

@item @b{abolish}(P)
Completely remove all clauses for the procedure with head P (which should be a term). For
example, the goal @REFILL

@example
    | ?- abolish( p(_, _, _) ).
@end example

@noindent
removes all clauses for the predicate @t{p}/3.

@item @b{abolish}(P, N)
Completely remove all clauses for the predicate P (which should be an atom) with arity N
(which should be an integer).@REFILL
@end table

@node Internal Database, State of the Program, Modification of the Program, Evaluable Predicates
@section Internal Database

@table @asis
@item @b{recorded}(Key, Term, Ref)
The internal database is searched for terms recorded under the key Key.  These terms are
successively unified with Term in the order they occur in the database; at the same time,
Ref is unified with the database reference of the recorded item.  The key must be given,
and may be an atom or complex term.  If it is a complex term, only the principal functor
is significant.@REFILL

@item @b{recorda}(Key, Term, Ref)
The term Term is recorded in the internal database as the first item for the key Key,
where Ref is its database reference.  The key must be given, and only its principal
functor is significant.@REFILL

@item @b{recordz}(Key, Term, Ref)
The term Term is recorded in the internal database as the last item for the key Key, where
Ref is its database reference.  The key must be given, and only its principal functor is
significant.@REFILL

@item @b{erase}(Clref)
The recorded item or clause whose database reference is Clref is deleted from the internal
database or program.  Clref should be instantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{instance}(Ref, Term)
A (most general) instance of the recorded term whose database reference is Ref is unified
with Term.  Ref must be instantiated to a database reference.  Note that @b{instance}/2
will not be able to access terms that have been erased.@REFILL
@end table

@node State of the Program, Environmental, Internal Database, Evaluable Predicates
@section Information about the State of the Program

@table @asis
@item @b{listing}
Lists in the current output stream the clauses for all the interpreted predicates in the
program, except predicates that are ``internal'', i.e. whose names begin with `kbd{$}' or `@kbd{_$}',
or which are provided as predefined (builtin or library) predicates.  A bug in the current
system is that even though the user is allowed to redefine such predicates, @b{listing}/0
does not know about such redefinitions, and will not list such predicates (they may,
however, be accessed through @b{listing}/1 if they are interpreted).@REFILL

@item @b{listing}(A)
The argument A may be a predicate specification of the form Name/Arity in which case only
the clauses for the specified predicate are listed.  Alternatively, it is possible for A
to be a list of predicate specifications, e.g.@REFILL

@example
    | ?- listing([concatenate/3, reverse/2, go/0]).
@end example

Only interpreted clauses, i.e. clauses created via @b{assert}, can be accessed through
@b{listing}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{current_atom}(Atom)
Generates (through backtracking) all currently known atoms, and unifies each in turn with
Atom.  However, atoms considered ``internal'' symbols, i.e. those whose names begin with $
or _$ are not returned.  The intrepid user who wishes to access such internal atoms as
well can use the goal @REFILL

@example
    ?- $current_atom(Atom, 1).
@end example

@item @b{current_functor}(Name, Term)
Generates (through backtracking) all currently known functors (which includes function and
predicate symbols), and for each one returns its name and most general term as Name and
Term respectively.  However, functors considered ``internal'' symbols, i.e.  those whose
names begin with @kbd{$} or @kbd{_$}, or which are provided as predefined predicates, are not returned
if both arguments to @b{current_functor}/2 are variables.  Internal symbols (of which
there are a great many) as well as external ones may be accessed via @REFILL

@example
    ?- $current_functor(Name, Term, 1).
@end example

A bug in the current implementation is that even though the user is allowed to redefine
``internal'' (builtin or library) predicates, @b{current_functor}/2 does not know whether
they have been redefined, and hence will not return such predicates if both arguments to
@b{current_functor}/2 are variables.@REFILL

@item @b{current_predicate}(Name, Term)
Generates (through backtracking) all currently known predicates, and for each one returns
its name and most general term as Name and Term respectively.  However, predicates
considered ``internal'', i.e. those whose names begin with @kbd{$} or @kbd{_$}, or which are provided
as predefined predicates, are not returned if both arguments to @b{current_predicate}/2
are variables.  Internal symbols (of which there are a great many) as well as external
ones may be accessed via @REFILL

@example
    ?- $current_predicate(Name, Term, 1).
@end example

A bug in the current implementation is that even though the user is allowed to redefine
``internal'' (builtin or library) predicates, @b{current_predicate}/2 does not know
whether they have been redefined, and hence will not return such predicates if both
arguments to @b{current_predicate}/2 are variables.@REFILL

@item @b{predicate_property}(Term, Property)
If Term is a term whose principal functor is a predicate, Property is unified with the
currently known properties of the corresponding predicate.  If Term is a variable, then it
is unified (successively, through backtracking) with the most general term for a predicate
whose known properties are unified with Property.  For example, all the interpreted
predicates in the program may be enumerated using @REFILL

@example
    ?- predicate_property(X, interpreted).
@end example

If the first argument to @b{predicate_property}/2 is uninstantiated at the time of the
call, ``internal'' predicates will not be returned.  A bug in the current implementation
is that even though the user is allowed to redefine such ``internal'' predicates,
@b{predicate_property}/2 does not know about such redefinitions, and will not return such
predicates if its first argument is uninstantiated.  Currently, the only properties that
are considered are interpreted and compiled.@REFILL
@end table

@node Environmental, Global Values, State of the Program, Evaluable Predicates
@section Environmental

@table @asis
@item @b{op}(priority, type, name)
Treat name as an operator of the stated type and priority (@pxref{Operators}).  name may
also be a list of names, in which all are to be treated as operators of the stated type
and priority.@REFILL

@item @b{break}
Causes the current execution to be suspended at the next procedure call.  Then the
message @REFILL

@example
                [  Break  (level  1) ]
@end example

@noindent
is displayed.  The interpreter is then ready to accept input as though it was at the top
level (except that at break level n > 0, the prompt is @code{@r{n}: ?- }).  If another call of
break is encountered, it moves up to level 2, and so on.  To close the break and resume
the execution which was suspended, type the END-OF-INPUT character.  Execution will be
resumed at the procedure call where it had been suspended.  Alternatively, the suspended
execution can be aborted by calling the evaluable predicate abort, which causes a return
to the top level.@REFILL

@item @b{abort}
Aborts the current execution, taking you back to top level.@REFILL

@item @b{save}(F)
The system saves the current state of the system into file F.@REFILL

@item @b{restore}(F)
The system restores the saved state in file F to be the current state.  One restriction
imposed by the current system is that various system parameters (e.g.  stack sizes,
permanent space, heap space, etc.) of the saved state have to be the same as that of the
current invocation.  Thus, it is not possible to save a state from an invocation where
50000 words of permanent space had been allocated, and then restore the same state in an
invocation with 100000 words of permanent space.@REFILL

@item @b{cputime}(X)
Unifies X with the time elapsed, in milliseconds, since the system was started
up.@REFILL

@item @b{$getenv}(Var,Val)
Val is unified with the value of the Unix environment variable Var.  Fails is Var is
undefined.@REFILL

@item @b{statistics}
Prints out the current allocations and amounts of space used for each of the four main
areas: the permanent area, the local stack, the global stack and the trail stack.  Does
not work well unless the simulator has been called with the -s option
(@pxref{Simulator Options}).@REFILL

@item @b{statistics}(Keyword, List)
Usually used with Keyword instantiated to a keyword, e.g. @samp{runtime}, and List
unbound.  It unifies List with a list of statistics determined by Keyword.  The keys and
values are summarized below.  Times are given in milliseconds and sizes are given in
bytes.@REFILL

@example
  KEYWORD               LIST

  runtime               [cpu time used by Prolog, cpu time since
                         last call to statistics/2]
  memory                [total virtual memory, 0]
  core                  ( same as for the keyword memory )
  program               [program space in use, program space free]
  heap                  ( same as for the keyword program )
  global_stack          [global stack in use, global stack free]
  local_stack           [local stack in use, local stack free]
  trail                 [trail stack in use, trail stack free]
  garbage_collection    [0, 0]
  stack_shifts          [0, 0]
@end example

@enumerate
@item
For the keyword @samp{memory} the second element of the returned list is
always 0.@REFILL

@item
For the keyword @samp{trail}, the second element of the returned list is the amount of
trail stack free.  This is similar to Sicstus Prolog (version 0.5), but different from
Quintus Prolog (version 1.6).@REFILL

@item
Currently, SB-Prolog does not have garbage collection or stack shifting, hence the list
values returned for these are [0, 0].@REFILL
@end enumerate

@item @b{nodynload}(P, N)
Flags the predicate P with arity N as one that should not be attempted to be dynamically
loaded if it is undefined.  If a predicate so flagged is undefined when a call to it is
encountered, the call fails quietly without trying to invoke the dynamic loader or giving
an error message.  P and N should be instantiated to an atom and an integer, respectively,
at the time of call to @b{nodynload}/2.@REFILL

@item @b{symtype}(T, N)
Unifies N with the ``internal type'' of the principal functor of the term T, which must be
instantiated at the time of the call.  N is bound to 0 if T does not have an entry point
defined (i.e. cannot be executed); to 1 if the principal functor of T is ``dynamic'', i.e.
has asserted code; to 2 if the principal functor for T is a compiled predicate; and 3 if T
denotes a buffer.  Thus, for example, if the predicate @b{p}/2 is a compiled predicate
which has been loaded into the system, the goal:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- symtype(p(_,_), X).
@end example

@noindent
will succeed binding X to 2; on the other hand, the goal:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- assert(q(a,b,c)), symtype(q(_,_,_), X).
@end example

@noindent
will succeed binding X to 1.

@item @b{system}(Call)
Calls the operating system with the atom Call as argument.  For example,
the call:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- system('ls').
@end example

@noindent
will produce a directory listing.  Since @b{system}/1 is executed by forking off a shell
process, it cannot be used, for example, to change the working directory of
the simulator.@REFILL

@item @b{syscall}(N, Args, Res)
Executes the Unix system call number N with arguments Args, and returns the result in Res.
N is an integer, and Args a Prolog list of the arguments to the system call.  For example,
to execute the system call @samp{creat(File,Mode)}, knowing that the syscall number for
the Unix command creat(2) is 8, we execute the goal @REFILL

@example
    | ?- syscall(8, [File, Mode], Des).
@end example

@noindent
where Des is the file descriptor returned by creat.  The syscall numbers for some Unix
system calls are given in the table below:@REFILL

@tex
\centerline{\vbox{\halign{\hfil\tt#&\hfil#\quad&\hfil\tt#&\hfil#\cr
exit & 1 & fork & 2 \cr
read & 3 & write & 4\cr
open & 5 & close & 6\cr
creat & 8 & link & 9\cr
unlink & 10 & chdir & 12\cr
chmod & 15 & lseek & 19\cr
access & 33 & kill & 37\cr
wait & 84 & socket & 97\cr
connect & 98 & accept & 99\cr
send & 101 & recv & 102\cr
bind & 104 & setsockopt & 105\cr
listen & 106 & recvmsg & 113\cr
sendmsg & 114 & getsockopt & 118\cr
recvfrom & 125 & sendto & 133\cr
socketpair & 135 & mkdir & 136\cr
rmdir & 137 & getsockname & 150\cr}}}
@end tex
@ifinfo
@example
          exit            1       fork            2
          read            3       write           4
          open            5       close           6
          creat           8       link            9
          unlink          10      chdir           12
          chmod           15      lseek           19
          access          33      kill            37
          wait            84      socket          97
          connect         98      accept          99
          send            101     recv            102
          bind            104     setsockopt      105
          listen          106     recvmsg         113
          sendmsg         114     getsockopt      118
          recvfrom        125     sendto          133
          socketpair      135     mkdir           136
          rmdir           137     getsockname     150
@end example
@end ifinfo
@end table

@node Global Values, Exotica, Environmental, Evaluable Predicates
@section Global Values

SB-Prolog has some primitives that permit the programmer to manipulate global values.
These are provided primarily as an efficiency hack, and needless to say, should be used
with a great deal of care.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{globalset}(Term)
Allows the user to save a global value.  Term must be bound to a compound term, say @code{p(V)}.
@code{V} must be a number or a constant or a variable.  If @code{V} is a number or a constant, the
effect of @code{@b{globalset}(p(V))} can be described as:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{retract(p(_)), assert(p(V)).}

@noindent
I.e., @code{p} is a predicate that when called will, from now on (until some other change
by @b{globalset}/1), deterministically return @code{V}.  If @code{V} is a variable, the
effect is to make @code{V} a global variable whose value is accessible by calling
@code{p}. For example, executing @code{@b{globalset}(p(X))} makes @code{X} a global
variable. @code{X} can be set by unification with some other term.  On backtracking,
@code{X} will be restored to its earlier value.@REFILL

@item @b{gennum}(Newnum)
@b{gennum}/1 sets its argument to a new integer every time it is invoked.@REFILL

@item @b{gensym}(C, Newsym)
@b{gensym}/2 sets its second argument to an atom whose name is made by concatenating the
name of the atom C to the current gennum number. This new constant is bound to Newsym.
For example, if the current gennum number is 37, then the call @REFILL

@example
    | ?- gensym(aaa,X)
@end example

@noindent
will succeed binding @t{X} to the atom @samp{aaa37}.
@end table

@node Exotica, , Global Values, Evaluable Predicates
@section Exotica

This section describes some low level routines that are sometimes useful in mucking around
with buffers.  These are for serious hackers only.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{$alloc_buff}(Size,Buff,Type,Supbuff,Retcode)
Allocates a buffer.  Size is the length (in bytes) of the buffer to allocate; Buff is the
buffer allocated, and should be unbound at the time of the call; Type indicates where to
allocate the buffer: a value of 0 indicates that the buffer is to be allocated in
permanent space, 1 that it should be on the heap, and 2 indicates that it should be
allocated from a larger heap buffer; Supbuff is the larger buffer to allocate a subbuffer
out of, and is only looked at if the value of Type is 2; Retcode is the return code: a
value of 0 indicates that the buffer has been allocated, while a value of 1 indicates
that the buffer could not be allocated due to lack of space.  The arguments Size, Type,
and Supbuff (if Type = 2) are input arguments, and should be bound at the time of the
call; Buff and Retcode are output arguments, and should be unbound at the time of the
call.@REFILL

@item @b{call_ref}(Call, Ref)
Calls the predicate whose database reference (prref) is Ref, using the literal Call as the
call.  This is similar to @b{call_ref}(Call, Ref, 0).@REFILL

@item @b{call_ref}(Call, Ref, Tr)
Calls the predicate whose database reference (prref) is Ref, using the literal Call as the
call.  Tr must be either 0 or 1: if Tr is 0 then the call Call is made assuming the
``trust'' optimization will be made; if Tr is 1 then the ``trust'' optimization is not
used, so that any new fact added before final failure will be seen by Call.  (Also, this
currently does not take advantage of any indexing that might have been constructed.) Call,
Ref and Tr are all input arguments, and should be instantiated at the time
of call.@REFILL

@item @b{$assertf_alloc_t}(Palist,Size)
Declares that each predicate in the list Palist of predicate/arity pairs (terms of the
form `/'(P,N) where P is a predicate symbol and N the arity of P) is to have any facts
asserted to them stored in a buffer on the heap, to be allocated here.  This allocates a
superbuffer of size Size on the heap.  Future assertions to these predicates will have
their clauses put in this buffer.  When this call is backtracked over, any clauses
asserted to these predicates are deallocated, and a subsequent call to any of those
predicates will cause the simulator to report an error and fail.  Both Palist and Size are
input arguments, and should be instantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_new_prref}(Prref,Where,Supbuff)
Creates an empty Prref, i.e. one with no facts in it. If called, it will simply fail.
Where indicates where the prref should be allocated: a value of 0 indicates the permanent
area, while a value of 2 indicates that it is to be allocated as a subbuffer.  Supbuff is
the superbuffer from which to allocate Prref if Where is 2.  Where should be instantiated
at the time of call, while Prref should be uninstantiated; in addition, if Where is 2,
Supbuff should be instantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_assert_fact}(Fact,Prref,AZ,Index,Clref,Where,Supbuff)
Fact is a fact to be asserted; Prref is a predicate reference to which to add the asserted
fact; AZ is either 0, indicating the fact should be inserted as the first clause in Prref,
or 1, indicating it should be inserted as the last; Index is 0 if no index is to be built,
or n if an index on the n[th] argument of the fact is to be used.  (Asserting at the
beginning of the chain with indexing is not yet supported.)  Where indicates where the
clref is to be allocated: a value of 0 indicates that it should be in the permanent area,
while a value of 2 indicates that it should be allocated as a subbuffer of Supbuff.  Clref
is returned and it is the clause reference of the asserted fact.  Fact, Prref, AZ, Index
and Where are input arguments, and should be instantiated at the time of call; in
addition, if Where is 2, then Supbuff should also be instantiated.  Clref is an output
argument, and should be uninstantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_add_clref}(Fact,Prref,AZ,Index,Clref,Where,Supbuff)
Adds the clref Clref to the prref Prref. Fact is the fact that has been compiled into
Clref (used only to get the arity and for indexing).  The other parameters are as for
@b{$db_assert_fact}/7.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_call_prref}(Call,Prref)
Calls the prref Prref using the literal Call as the call.  The call is done by simply
branching to the first clause.  New facts added to Prref after the last fact has been
retrieved by Call, but before Call is failed through, will not be used.  Both Call and
Prref are input arguments, and should be instantiated at the time of call.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_call_prref_s}(Call,Prref)
This also calls the prref Prref using Call as the call.  The difference from
@b{$db_call_prref} is that this does not use the ``trust'' optimization, so that any new
fact added before final failure will be seen by Call.  (Also, this currently does not take
advantage of any indexing that might have been constructed, while @b{$db_call_prref}
does.)  Both Call and Prref are input arguments, and should be instantiated at the time of
call.@REFILL

@item @b{$db_get_clauses}(Prref,Clref,Dir)
This returns, nondeterministically, all the clause references Clref for clauses asserted
to prref Prref.  If Dir is 0, then the first clref on the list is returned first; if Dir
is 1, then they are returned in reverse order.  Prref and Dir are input arguments, and
should be instantiated at the time of call; Clref is an output argument, and should be
uninstantiated at the time of call.@REFILL
@end table

@node Debugging, Simulator, Evaluable Predicates, Top
@chapter Debugging

@menu
* High Level Tracing::
* Low Level Tracing::
@end menu

@node High Level Tracing, Low Level Tracing,, Debugging
@section High Level Tracing

The preferred method of tracing execution is through the predicate @b{trace}/1.  This
predicate takes as argument a term P/N, where P is a predicate name and N its arity, and
sets a ``trace point'' on the corresponding predicate; it can also be given a list of such
terms, in which case a trace point is set on each member of the list.  For example,
executing @REFILL

@example
    | ?- trace(pred1/2), trace([pred2/3, pred3/2]).
@end example

@noindent
sets trace points on predicates @t{pred1}/2, @t{pred2}/3 and @t{pred3}/2.  Only those
predicates are traced that have trace points set on them.@REFILL

If all the predicates in a file are to be traced, it is usually convenient to use the
@code{PredList} parameter of @b{compile}/4 or @b{consult}/3, e.g.:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile(foo, 'foo.out', [t,v], Preds), load('foo.out'), trace(Preds).
@r{or}
    | ?- consult(foo, [v], Preds), trace(Preds).
@end example

Notice that in the first case, the @code{t} compiler option (@pxref{Compiler Options})
should be specified in order to turn off certain assembler optimizations and facilitate
tracing.  In the second case, the same effect may be achieved by specifying the @code{t}
option to @bb{consult}.@REFILL

The trace points set on predicates may be overwritten by loading byte code files via
@b{load}/1, and in this case it may be necessary to explicitly set trace points again on
the loaded predicates.  This does not happen with @b{consult}: predicates that were being
traced continue to have trace points set after consulting.@REFILL

The tracing facilities of SB-Prolog are in many ways very similar to those of C-Prolog.
However, leashing is not supported, and only those predicates can be traced which have had
trace points set on them through @b{trace}/1.  This makes @b{trace}/1 and @b{spy}/1 very
similar: essentially, trace amounts to two levels of spy points.  In SB-Prolog, tracing
occurs at Call (i.e. entry to a predicate), successful Exit from a clause, and Failure of
the entire call.  The tracing options available during debugging are the following:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @t{c}, NEWLINE: Creep
Causes the system to single-step to the next port (i.e.  either the entry to a traced
predicate called by the executed clause, or the success or failure exit from
that clause).@REFILL

@item @t{a}: Abort
Causes execution to abort and control to return to the top level
interpreter.@REFILL

@item @t{b}: Break
Calls the evaluable predicate break, thus invoking recursively a new incarnation of the
system interpreter.  The command prompt at break level n is:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{@r{n}: ?-}

The user may return to the previous break level by entering the system end-of-file
character (e.g.  ctrl-D), or typing in the atom @samp{end_of_file}; or to the top level
interpreter by typing in @b{abort}.@REFILL

@item @t{f}: Fail
Causes execution to fail, thus transferring control to the Fail port of the current
execution.@REFILL

@item @t{h}: Help
Displays the table of debugging options.@REFILL

@item @t{l}: Leap
Causes the system to resume running the program, only stopping when a spy-point is reached
or the program terminates.  This allows the user to follow the execution at a higher level
than exhaustive tracing.@REFILL

@item @t{n}: Nodebug
Turns off debug mode.@REFILL

@item @t{q}: Quasi-skip
This is like Skip except that it does not mask out spy points.@REFILL

@item @t{r}: Retry (fail)
Transfers to the Call port of the current goal.  Note, however, that side effects, such as
database modifications etc., are not undone.@REFILL

@item @t{s}: Skip
Causes tracing to be turned off for the entire execution of the procedure.  Thus, nothing
is seen until control comes back to that procedure, either at the Success or the Failure
port.@REFILL
@end table

Other predicates that are useful in debugging are:

@table @asis
@item @b{untrace}(Preds)
where Preds is a term P/N, where P is a predicate name and N its arity, or a list of such
terms.  Turns off tracing on the specified predicates.  Preds must be instantiated at the
time of the call.@REFILL

@item @b{spy}(Preds)
where Preds is a term P/N, where P is a predicate name and N its arity, or a list of such
terms.  Sets spy points on the specified predicates.  Preds must be instantiated at the
time of the call.@REFILL

@item @b{nospy}(Preds)
where Preds is a term P/N, where P is a predicate name and N its arity, or a list of such
terms.  Removes spy points on the specified predicates.  Preds must be instantiated at the
time of the call.@REFILL

@item @b{debug}
Turns on debugging mode.  This causes subsequent execution of predicates with trace or spy
points to be traced, and is a no-op if there are no such predicates.  The predicates
@b{trace}/1 and @b{spy}/1 cause debugging mode to be turned on
automatically.@REFILL

@item @b{nodebug}
Turns off debugging mode.  This causes trace and spy points to be ignored.@REFILL

@item @b{debugging}
Displays information about whether debug mode is on or not, and lists predicates that have
trace points or spy points set on them.@REFILL

@item @b{tracepreds}(L)
Binds L to a list of terms P/N where the predicate P of arity N has a trace point set on
it.@REFILL

@item @b{spypreds}(L)
Binds L to a list of terms P/N where the predicate P of arity N has a spy point set
on it.@REFILL
@end table

There is one known bug in the package: attempts to set trace points, via @b{trace}/1, on
system and library predicates that are used by the trace package can cause bizarre
behaviour.@REFILL

@node Low Level Tracing,, High Level Tracing, Debugging
@section Low Level Tracing

SB-Prolog also provides a facility for low level tracing of execution.  This can be
activated by invoking the simulator with the @code{-T} option, or through the predicate
@b{$trace}/0.  It causes trace information to be printed out at every call (including
those to system trap handlers).  The volume of such trace information can very become
large very quickly, so this method of tracing is not recommended in general.@REFILL

Low level tracing may be turned off using the predicate @b{untrace}/0.

@node Simulator, Compiler, Debugging, Top
@chapter The Simulator

The simulator resides in the SB-Prolog system directory @file{sim}.  The following
sections describe various aspects of the simulator.@REFILL

@menu
* Invoking the Simulator::
* Simulator Options::
* Interrupts::
@end menu

@node Invoking the Simulator, Simulator Options,, Simulator
@section Invoking the Simulator

The simulator is invoked by the command

@CENTER @t{sbprolog} @i{bc_file}

where `@i{bc_file}' is a byte code file resulting from the compilation of a Prolog
program.  In almost all cases, the user will wish to interact with the SB-Prolog query
evaluator, in which case `@i{bc_file}' will be @file{$readloop}, and the command will be:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{sbprolog Path/$readloop}

@noindent
where @t{Path} is the path to the directory containing the command interpreter @file{$readloop}.
This directory, typically, is the system directory @file{modlib}.@REFILL

The command interpreter reads in a query typed in by the user, evaluates it and prints the
answer(s), repeating this until it encounters an end-of-file (the standard end-of-file
character on the system, e.g. ctrl-D), or the user types in @code{end_of_file} or @code{halt}.@REFILL

The user should ensure that the the directory containing the executable file @file{sim}
(typically, the system directory @file{sim}) is included in the shell variable path; if
not, the full path to the simulator will have to be specified.@REFILL

In general, the simulator may be invoked with a variety of options, as
follows:@REFILL

@example
    sbprolog -options @i{bc_file}
@r{or}
    sbprolog -option<1> -option<2> ... -option<n> @i{bc_file}
@end example

The options recognized by the simulator are described below.@REFILL

When called with a byte code file `@i{bc_file}', the simulator begins execution with the
first clause in that file.  The first clause in such a file, therefore, should be a clause
without any arguments in the head (otherwise, the simulator will attempt to dereference
argument pointers in the head that are really pointing into deep space, and usually come
to a sad end).  If the user is executing a file in this manner rather than using the
command interpreter, he should also be careful to include the undefined predicate handler
@b{_$undefined_pred}/1, which is normally defined in the file @file{modlib/$init_sys.P}.@REFILL

@node Simulator Options, Interrupts, Invoking the Simulator, Simulator
@section Simulator Options

The following is a list of options recognized by the simulator.@REFILL

@table @t
@item T
Generates a trace at entry to each called routine.

@item d
Produces a disassembled dump of `@i{bc_file} into a file named @file{dump.pil} and
exits.@REFILL

@item n
Adds machine addresses when producing trace and dump.

@item s
Maintains information for the builtin @b{statistics}/0.  Default: off.

@item m @r{size}
Allocates size words (4 bytes) of space to the local stack and heap together.  Default:
100000.@REFILL

@item p @r{size}
Allocates size words of space to the program area.  Default: 100000.@REFILL

@item b @r{size}
Allocates size words of space to the trail stack.  Default: m/5, where m is the amount of
space allocated to the local stack and heap together.  This parameter, if specified, must
follow the @code{-m} parameter.@REFILL
@end table

As an example, the command:

@CENTER @t{sbprolog -s -p 60000 -m 150000 \$readloop}

@noindent
starts the simulator executing the command interpreter with 60000 bytes of program space,
150000 bytes of local and global stack space and (by default) 30000 bytes of trail stack
space; the @code{s} option also results in statistics information being maintained.@REFILL

@node Interrupts,, Simulator Options, Simulator
@section Interrupts

SB-Prolog provides a facility for exception handling using user-definable interrupt
handlers.  This can be used both for external interrupts, e.g. those generated from the
keyboard by the user or from signals other processes; or internal traps, e.g.  those
caused by stack overflows, encountering undefined predicates, etc.  For example, the
``undefined predicate'' interrupt is handled, by default, by the predicate
@b{_$undefined_pred}/1, which is defined in the files @file{modlib/src/$init_sys.P} and
@file{modlib/src/$readloop.P}. The default action on encountering an undefined predicate
is to attempt to dynamically load a file whose name matches that of the undefined
predicate.  However, the user may easily alter this behaviour by redefining the undefined
predicate handler.@REFILL

In general, interrupts are handled by the predicate @b{_$interrupt}/2: a call to this
predicate is of the form @b{_$interrupt}(Call, Code), where Call is the call that
generated the interrupt, and Code is an integer indicating the nature of the interrupt.
For each interrupt code, the interrupt handler then calls a handler that is designed to
handle that particular kind of interrupt.  At this point, the following interrupt codes
have predefined meanings:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item 0
undefined predicate;

@item 1
keyboard interrupt ( ^C );

@item 2
stack overflow.
@end table

Other interrupt codes may be incorporated by modifying the definition of the predicate
@b{_$interrupt}/2 in the file @file{modlib/src/$readloop.P}.@REFILL

Interrupts during execution are signalled from within the WAM simulator.  The general
method for raising an interrupt is using the function @code{set_intercode} in the file
@file{sim/sub_inst.c}: to raise an interrupt whose code is n, the line:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{lpcreg = set_intercode(@r{n});}

@noindent
is added to the appropriate place in the main loop of the interpreter, defined in
@file{sim/main.c}.@REFILL

@node Compiler, Libraries, Simulator, Top
@chapter The Compiler

The compiler translates Prolog source files into byte-code object files.  It is written
entirely in Prolog.  The byte code for the compiler can be found in the SB-Prolog system
directory @file{cmplib}, with the source code resident in @file{cmplib/src}.@REFILL

Byte code files may be concatenated together to produce other byte code files.  Thus, for
example, if @file{foo1} and @file{foo2} are byte code files resulting from the compilation of two Prolog
source programs, then the file @file{foo}, obtained by executing the shell command:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{cat foo1 foo2 > foo}

@noindent
is a byte code file as well, and may be loaded and executed.  In this case, loading and
executing the file @file{foo} would give the same result as loading @file{foo1} and
@file{foo2} separately, which in turn would be the same as concatenating the original
source files and compiling this larger file.  This makes it easier to compile large
programs: one need only break them into smaller pieces, compile the individual pieces, and
concatenate the byte files together.@REFILL

The following sections describe the various aspects of the compiler in more
detail.@REFILL

@menu
* Invoking the Compiler::
* Compiler Options::
* Assembly::
* Compiler Directives::
@end menu

@node Invoking the Compiler, Compiler Options,, Compiler
@section Invoking the Compiler

The compiler is invoked through the Prolog predicate @b{compile}:

@example
    | ?- compile(InFile [, OutFile ] [, OptionsList ]).
@end example

@noindent
where optional parameters are enclosed in brackets.  @code{InFile} is the name of the input (i.e.
source) file; @code{OutFile} is the name of the output file (i.e. byte code) file; @code{OptionsList} is
a list of compiler options (see below).@REFILL

The input and output file names must be Prolog atoms, i.e.  either begin with a lower case
letter or dollar sign `@kbd{$}', and consist only of letters, digits, and underscores; or, be
enclosed within single quotes.  If the output file name is not specified, it defaults to
@file{InFile.out}.  The list of options, if specified, is a Prolog list, i.e. a term of the form:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{[ option<1>, option<2>, @dots{}, option<n> ]}

@noindent
If left unspecified, it defaults to the empty list @t{[]}.

In fact, the output file name and the options list may be specified in any order.  Thus,
for example, the queries:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile('/usr/debray/foo', foo_out, [v]).
@r{and}
    | ?- compile('/usr/debray/foo', [v], foo_out).
@end example

@noindent
are equivalent, and specify that the Prolog source file @file{/usr/debray/foo} is to be
compiled in verbose mode (@pxref{Compiler Options}), and that the byte code is to be
generated into the file @file{foo_out}.@REFILL

The @bb{compile} predicate may also be called with a fourth parameter:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile(InFile, OutFile, OptionsList, PredList).
@end example

@noindent
where @code{InFile}, @code{OutFile} and @code{OptionsList} are as before; @b{compile}/4
unifies @code{PredList} with a list of terms P/N denoting the predicates defined in
@code{InFile}, where P is a predicate name and N its arity. @code{PredList}, if specified,
is usually given as an uninstantiated variable; its principal use is for setting trace
points on the predicates in the file (@pxref{Debugging}), e.g. by executing:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- compile('/usr/debray/foo', foo_out, [v], L), load(foo_out), trace(L).
@end example

Notice that @code{PredList} can only appear in @b{compile}/4.

@node Compiler Options, Assembly, Invoking the Compiler, Compiler
@section Compiler Options

The following options are currently recognized by the compiler:

@table @t
@item a
Specifies that an ``assembler'' file is to be created.  The name of the assembler file is
obtained by appending @file{.asl} to the source file name.  While the writing out of assembly
code slows down the compilation process to some extent, it allows the assembler to do a
better job of optimizing away indirect subroutine linkages (since in this case the
assembler has assembly code for the entire program to work with at once, not just a single
predicate).  This results in code that is faster and more compact.@REFILL

@item d
Dumps expanded macros to the user (@pxref{Macro Expander Options}).

@item e
Expand macros (@pxref{Macro Expander Options}).

@item t
If specified, turns off assembler optimizations that eliminate indirect branches through
the symbol table in favour of direct branches.  This is useful in debugging compiled code.
It is necessary if the extension table feature is to be used.@REFILL

@item v
If specified, compiles in ``verbose'' mode, which causes messages regarding progress of
compilation to be printed out.@REFILL
@end table

@node Assembly, Compiler Directives, Compiler Options, Compiler
@section Assembly

The SB-Prolog assembler can be invoked by loading the compiler and using the predicate
@b{$asm}/3:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- $asm(InFile, OutFile, OptionsList).
@end example

where @code{InFile} is a Prolog atom which is the name of a WAM assembly source file (e.g.
the @file{.asl} file generated when a Prolog program is compiled with the @code{a}
option), @code{OutFile} is an atom which is the name of the intended byte code file, and
@code{OptionsList} is a list of options.  The options recognized by the assembler
are:@REFILL

@table @t
@item v
``Verbose'' mode.  Prints out information regarding progress of assembly.@REFILL

@item t
``Trace''.  If specified, the assembler generates code to force procedure calls to branch
indirectly via the symbol table, instead of using a direct branch.  This is useful for
tracing compiled code.  It is necessary if the extension table feature is to be
used.@REFILL
@end table

The assembler is intended primarily to support the compiler, so the assembly language
syntax is quirky in places.  The interested reader is advised to look at the assembly
files resulting from compilation with the @code{a} option for more on SB-Prolog assembler
syntax.@REFILL

@node Compiler Directives,, Assembly, Compiler
@section Compiler Directives

@menu
* Mode Declarations::
* Indexing Directives::
@end menu

@node Mode Declarations, Indexing Directives,, Compiler Directives
@subsection Mode Declarations

The user may declare input and output arguments of predicates using mode declarations.
These declarations, for an n-ary predicate @code{p}, are of the form @REFILL

@CENTER @t{:- mode p( Mode ).}

@noindent
where @code{Mode} consists of n mode values; or

@CENTER @t{:- mode(p, n, ModeList)}

@noindent
where @code{ModeList} is a list of mode values of length n.  Mode values may be the
following:@REFILL

@table @t
@item c@r{,} ++
Indicates that the corresponding argument position is always a ground term in any call to
the predicate.  The argument is therefore an input argument.@REFILL

@item nv@r{,} +
Indicates that the corresponding argument position is always a nonvariable term (i.e.  is
instantiated) in any call in any call to the predicate.  The argument is therefore an
input argument.@REFILL

@item f@r{,} -
Indicates that the corresponding argument position is always an uninstantiated variable in
any call to the predicate.  The argument is therefore an output argument.@REFILL

@item d@r{,} ?
Indicates that the corresponding argument may be any term in calls to the
predicate.@REFILL
@end table

For example, a 3-ary predicate @code{p} whose first argument is always a ground term in a call,
whose second argument is always uninstantiated, and whose third argument can be any term,
may have its mode declared as:@REFILL

@example
    :- mode p(++, -, d).
@r{or as}
    :- mode(p, 3, [c, f, d]).
@end example

Currently, mode information is used by the compiler in two ways.  First, it often allows
more compact code to be generated.  The second use is in guiding program transformations
that allow faster code to be generated.  For example, the predicate:@REFILL

@example
    part([], _, [], []).
    part([E|L], M, [E|U1], U2) :- E =< M, part(L, M, U1, U2).
    part([E|L], M, U1, [E|U2]) :- E  > M, part(L, M, U1, U2).
@end example

@noindent
executes about 30% faster with the mode declaration

@example
    :- mode part(++, ++, -, -).
@end example

@noindent
than without.

@node Indexing Directives,, Mode Declarations, Compiler Directives
@subsection Indexing Directives

The compiler usually generates an index on the principal functor of the first argument of
a predicate.  The user may direct the compiler to generate an index on any other argument
by means of an indexing directive.  This is of the form @REFILL

@example
    :- index(Pred, Arity, IndexArg)
@end example

@noindent
indicating that an index should be created on the @code{IndexArg@r{[th.]}} argument of the predicate
@code{Pred@r{/}Arity}.  All of the values @code{Pred}, @code{Arity} and @code{IndexArg} should be bound in the directive:
@code{Pred} should be an atom, @code{Arity} a nonnegative integer, and @code{IndexArg} an integer between 0 and
@code{Arity}.  If @code{IndexArg} is 0, then no index is created for that predicate.  As an example, if
we wished to create an index on the third argument of a 5-ary predicate @code{foo}, the compiler
directive would be:@REFILL

@example
    :- index(foo, 5, 3).
@end example

An index directive may be placed anywhere in the file containing the predicate it refers
to.@REFILL

@node Libraries, Macros, Compiler, Top
@chapter Libraries

To describe how libraries are currently supported in our system, we must describe the
@b{_$undefined_pred}/1 interrupt handler.  The system keeps a table of libraries and
routines that are needed from each.  When a predicate is found to be undefined, the table
is searched to see if it is defined by some library file.  If so, that file is loaded (if
it hasn't been previously loaded) and the association is made between the routine name as
defined in the library file, and the routine name as used by the invoker.@REFILL

The table of libraries and needed routines is:

@example
    @b{defined_mods}(Modname, [pred<1>/arity<1>, @dots{}, pred<n>/arity<n>]).
@end example

@noindent
where @code{Modname} is the name of the library.  It exports n predicate definitions.  The
first exported pred is of arity @code{arity<1>}, and needs to be invoked by the name of
@code{pred<1>}.@REFILL

The table of libraries that have already been loaded is given by

@example
    @b{loaded_mods}(Modname).
@end example

A library file is a file of predicate definitions, together with a fact defining a list of
predicates exported by it; and a set of facts, each of which specifies, for some other
library file, the predicates imported from that library file.  For example, consider a
library name @code{p}. It contains a single fact, named @bb{p_export}, that is true of the list of
predicate/arity's that are exported.  E.g.@REFILL

@example
    @b{p_export}([p1/2, p2/4]).
@end example

@noindent
indicates that the module @code{p} exports the predicates @t{p1}/2 and @t{p2}/4.  For each
library @code{m} which contains predicates needed by the library @code{p}, there is a fact for
@bb{p_use}, describing what library is needed and the names of the predicates defined there
that are needed.  For example, if library @code{p} needs to import predicates @t{ip1}/2 and @t{ip2}/3
from library @code{q}, there would be a fact:@REFILL

@example
    @b{p_use}(q,[ip1/2, ip2/3])
@end example

@noindent
where @code{q} is a module that exports two predicates: one 2-ary and one 3-ary.  This list
corresponds to the export list of library @code{q}.@REFILL

The correspondence between the predicates in the export list of an exporting library, and
those in the import or use list of a library which imports one or more of them, is by
position, i.e. the predicate names at the exporting and importing names may be different,
and the association between names in the two lists is by the position in the list.  If the
importing library does not wish to import one or more of the predicates exported by the
exporting module, it may put an anonymous variable in the corresponding position in its
use list.  Thus, for example, if library @code{p} above had wished to import only the predicate
@t{ip2}/3 from library @code{q}, the corresponding use fact would be:@REFILL

@example
    @b{p_use}(q, [_, ip2/3]).
@end example

The initial set of predicates and the libraries from which they are to be loaded is set up
by an initial call to @b{$prorc}/0 (see the SB-Prolog system file
@file{modlib/src/$prorc.P}).  This predicate makes initial calls to the predicate
@bb{$define_mod} which set up the tables described above so that the use of standard
predicates will cause the correct libraries to be loaded in the @bb{_$undefined_pred}
routine, and the correct names to be used.@REFILL

@node Macros, Extension Tables, Libraries, Top
@chapter Macros

SB-Prolog features a facility for the definition and expansion of macros that is fully
compatible with the runtime system.  Its basic mechanism is a simple partial evaluator.
It is called by both @bb{consult} and @bb{compile}, so that macro expansion occurs independently of
whether the code is interpreted or compiled (but not when asserted).  Moreover, the macro
definitions are retained as clauses at runtime, so that invocation of macros via
@b{call}/1 at runtime (or from asserted clauses) does not pose a problem.  This means,
however, that if the same macro is used in many different files, it will be loaded more
than once, thus leading to wasted space.  This ought to be thought about and fixed. @REFILL

The source for the macro expander is in the SB-Prolog system file
@file{modlib/src/$mac.P}.@REFILL

@menu
* Defining Macros::
* Macro Expander Options::
@end menu

@node Defining Macros, Macro Expander Options,, Macros
@section Defining Macros

`Macros', or predicates to be evaluated at compile-time, are defined by clauses of the
form @REFILL

@CENTER Head ::- Body

where facts have `true' as their body.  The partial evaluator will expand any call to a
predicate defined by ::-/2 that unifies with the head of only one clause in ::-/2. If a
call unifies with the head of more than one clause in ::-/2, it will not be expanded
Notice that this is not a fundamental restriction, since `;' is permitted in the body of a
clause.  The partial evaluator also converts each definition of the form:@REFILL

@CENTER Head ::- Body.

@noindent
to a clause of the form

@CENTER Head :- Body.

@noindent
and adds this second clause to the other ``normal'' clauses that were read from the file.
This ensures that calls to the macro at runtime, e.g. through @b{call}/1 or from
unexpanded calls in the program do not cause any problems.@REFILL

The partial evaluator is actually a Prolog interpreter written `purely' in Prolog, i.e.,
variable assignments are explicitly handled.  This is necessary to be able to handle
impure constructs such as `@b{var}(X), X=a'.  As a result this is a very slow Prolog
evaluator.@REFILL

Since naive partial evaluation can go into an infinite loop, SB-Prolog's partial evaluator
maintains a depth-bound and will not expand recursive calls deeper than that.  The depth
is determined by the @b{globalset} predicate @b{$mac_depth}.  The default value for
@b{$mac_depth} is 50 This can be changed to some other value n by executing @REFILL

@example
    | ?- globalset($mac_depth(n)).
@end example

@node Macro Expander Options,, Defining Macros, Macros
@section Macro Expander Options

The following options are recognized by the macro expander:

@table @t
@item d
Dumps all clauses to the user after expansion.  Useful for debugging.@REFILL

@item e
Expand macros.  If omitted, the expander simply converts each ::-/2 clause
to a normal :-/2 clause.

@item v
``Verbose'' mode.  Prints macros that are/are not being expanded.@REFILL
@end table

@node Extension Tables, Definite Clause Grammars, Macros, Top
@chapter Extension Tables: Memo Relations

Extension tables store the calls and answers for a predicate. If a call has been made
before, answers are retrieved from the extension table instead of being recomputed.
Extension tables provide a caching mechanism for Prolog. In addition, extension tables
affect the termination characteristics of recursive programs. Some Prolog programs, which
are logically correct, enter an infinite loop due to recursive predicates.  An extension
table saved on recursive predicates can find all answers (provided the set of such answers
is finite) and terminate for some logic programs for which Prolog's evaluation strategy
enters an infinite loop. Iterations over the extension table execution strategy provides
complete evaluation of queries over function-free Horn clause programs.@REFILL

To be able to use the simple extension table evaluation on a set of predicates, the source
file should either be consulted, or compiled with the @code{t} option (the @code{t} option keeps the
assembler from optimizing subroutine linkage and allows the extension table facility to
intercept calls to predicates).@REFILL

To use extension table execution, all predicates that are to be saved in the extension
table must be passed to @b{et}/1. For example:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- et([pred1/1, pred2/2]), et(pred3/2)
@end example

@noindent
will set up ``ET-points'' for the for predicates @t{pred1}/1, @code{pred2}/2 and
@code{pred3}/2, which will cause extension tables for these predicates to be maintained
during execution. At the time of the call to @b{et}/1, these predicates must be defined,
either by having been loaded, or through @bb{consult}.@REFILL

The predicate @b{noet}/1 takes a list of predicate/arity pairs for which ET-points should
be deleted.  Notice that once an ET-point has been set up for a predicate, it will be
maintained unless explicitly deleted via @b{noet}/1.  If the definition of a predicate
which has an ET-point defined is to be updated, the ET-point must first be deleted via
@b{noet}/1.  The predicate can then be reloaded and a new ET-point established.  This is
enforced by the failure of the goal ``@b{et}(P/N)'' if an ET-point already exists for the
argument predicate.  In this case, the following error message will be displayed:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{*et* already defined for:} P/N

There are, in fact, two extension table algorithms: a simple one, which simply caches
calls to predicates which have ET-points defined; and a complete ET algorithm, which
iterates the simple extension table algorithm until no more answers can be found.  The
simple algorithm is more efficient than the complete one; however, the simple algorithm is
not complete for certain especially nasty forms of mutual recursion, while the complete
algorithm is.  To use the simple extension table algorithm, predicates can simply be
called as usual.  The complete extension table algorithm may be used via the query:@REFILL

@example
    | ?- et_star(Query).
@end example

The extension table algorithm is intended for predicates that are ``essentially pure'',
and results are not guaranteed for code using impure code.  The extension table algorithm
saves only those answers which are not instances of what is already in the table,
and uses these answers if the current call is an instance of a call already made.  For
example, if a call @t{p(X, Y)}, with @t{X} and @t{Y} uninstantiated, is encountered and
inserted into the extension table, then a subsequent call @code{p(X, b)} will be computed
using the answers for @t{p(X, Y)} already in the extension table.  Notice that this might
not work if @b{var}/@b{nonvar} tests are used on the second argument in the evaluation of
@t{p}.@REFILL

Another problem with using impure code is that if an ET predicate is cut over, then the
saved call implies that all answers for that predicate were computed, but there are only
partial results in the ET because of the cut.  So on a subsequent call the incomplete
extension table answers are used when all answers are expected.@REFILL

@example
    r(X,Y) :- p(X,Y),q(Y,Z),!,fail.
    | ?-  r(X,Y) ; p(X,Y).
@end example

Let p be an ET predicate whose evaluation yields many tuples.  In the evaluation of the
query, r(X,Y) makes a call to p(X,Y).  Assuming that there is a tuple such that q(Y,Z)
succeeds with the first p tuple then the evaluation of p is cut over. The call to p(X,Y)
in the query uses the extension table because of the previous call in the evaluation of
r(X,Y). Only one answer is found, whereas the relation p contains many tuples, so the
computation is not complete.  Note that ``cuts'' used within the evaluation of an ET
predicate are ok, as long as they don't cut over the evaluation of another ET predicate.
The evaluation of the predicate that uses cuts does not cut over any et processing (such
as storing or retrieving answers) so that the tuples that are computed are saved. In the
following example, the ET is used to generate prime numbers where an ET point is put on
@b{prime}/1.@REFILL

@example
    prime(I) :- globalset(globalgenint(2)),fail. /* Generating Primes */
    prime(I) :- genint(I), not(div(I)).
    div(I) :- prime(X), 0 is I mod X.

    genint(N) :-
        repeat,
            globalgenint(N),
            N1 is N+1,
            globalset(globalgenint(N1)).
@end example

The following summarizes the library predicates supporting the extension table
facility:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{et}(L)
Sets up an ET-point on the predicates L, which causes calls and anwers to these predicates
to be saved in an ``extension table''.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is a
predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L
must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call
to @b{et}/1.  Gives error messages and fails if any of the predicates in L is undefined,
or if an ET-point already exists on any of them; in this case, no ET-point is set up on
any of the predicates in L.@REFILL

@item @b{et_star}(Goal)
Invokes the complete extension table algorithm on the goal Goal.@REFILL

@item @b{et_points}(L)
Unifies L with a list of predicates for which an ET-point is defined.  L is the empty list
[] if there are no ET-points defined.@REFILL

@item @b{noet}(L)
Deletes ET-points on the predicates specified in L.  L is either a term P/N, where P is
the name of a predicate and N its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.
Gives error messages and fails if there is no ET-point on any of the predicates specified
in L.  Deleting an ET-point for a predicate also removes the calls and answers stored in
the extension table for that predicate.  The extension tables for all predicates for which
ET-points are defined may be deleted using @b{et_points}/1 in conjunction with @b{noet}/1.
L must be instantiated at the time of the call to @b{noet}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{et_remove}(L)
Removes both calls and answers for the predicates specified in L.  In effect, this results
in the extension table for these predicates to be set to empty.  L must be instantiated at
the time of the call to either a term P/N, where P is a predicate with arity N, or a list
of such terms.  An error occurs if any of the predicates in L does not have an ET-point
set.@REFILL

All extension tables can be emptied by using @b{et_points}/1 in conjunction with
@iftex
{@bf et_@discretionary{}{}{}re@-move}/1
@end iftex
@ifinfo
@b{et_remove}/1.@REFILL
@end ifinfo

@item @b{et_answers}(P/N, Term)
Retrieves the answers stored in the extension table for the predicate P/N in Term one at a
time.  Term is of the form P(t<1>, ..., t<N>).  An error results and @b{et_answers}/2 fails if
P/N is not fully specified (ground), or if P/N does not have an ET-point
set.@REFILL

@item @b{et_calls}(P/N, Term)
Retrieves the calls stored in the extension table for the predicate P/N in Term one at a
time.  Term is of the form P(t<1>, ..., t<N>).  An error results and 2b{et_calls}/2 fails if
P/N is not fully specified (ground), or if P/N does not have an ET-point
set.@REFILL
@end table

@node Definite Clause Grammars, Profiling Programs, Extension Tables, Top
@chapter Definite Clause Grammars

Definite clause grammars are an extension of context free grammars, and may be conveniently
expressed in Prolog.  A grammar rule in Prolog has the form @REFILL

@CENTER Head @t{-->} Body.

@noindent
with the interpretation ``a possible form for Head is Body''.  Extra conditions, in the
form of explicit Prolog literals or control constructs such as if-then-else (@samp{->}) or cut
(@samp{!}), may be included in Body.@REFILL

The syntax of DCGs supported by SB-Prolog is as follows:

@enumerate
@item
A non-terminal symbol may be any Prolog term other than a variable.@REFILL

@item
A terminal symbol may be any Prolog term.  To distinguish terminals from nonterminals, a
sequence of terminal symbols @REFILL

@CENTER @t{a, b, c, d, @dots{}}

is written as a Prolog list @t{[a, b, c, d, @dots{} ]}, with the empty sequence written as the
empty list @t{[]}.  If the terminal symbols are ASCII character codes, they can be written (as
elsewhere) as strings.@REFILL

@item
Extra consitions, in the form of Prolog literals, can be included in the right-hand side
of a rule by enclosing such conditions in curly braces, { and }.  E.g., one can
write:@REFILL

@CENTER natnum(X) @t{-->} @{integer(X), X >= 0@}.

@item
The left hand side of a rule consists of a single nonterminal.  Notice that ``push-back
lists'' are thus not supported.@REFILL

@item
The right hand side of a rule may contain alternatives (written using the disjunction
operator @samp{;} or @samp{|}), and control primitives such as if-then-else (@samp{->}),
@b{not}/1 and cut (@samp{!}).  The use of @b{not}/1 on the right hand side of grammar
rules is not recommended, however, because their semantics in this context is murky at
best.  All other control primitives, e.g. @b{repeat}/0, must explicitly be enclosed within
curly braces if they are not to be interpreted as nonterminals.@REFILL
@end enumerate

Except for the restriction of lists of terminals in the left hand sides of rules, the
translation of DCGs in SB-Prolog is very similar to that in Quintus Prolog.@REFILL

Library predicates supporting DCGs are the following:

@table @asis
@item @b{dcg}(Rule, Clause)
Succeeds if the DCG rule Rule corresponds to the Prolog clause Clause.  At the time of
call, Rule must be bound to a term whose principal functor is @t{-->}/2.@REFILL

@item @b{phrase}(Phrase, List)
The usual way to commence execution of grammar rules.  The list List is a phrase (i.e.,
sequence of terminals) generated by Phrase according to the current grammar rules.  Phrase
is a nonterminal (in general, the right hand side of a grammar rule), and must be
instantiated to a nonvariable term in the call.  If List is bound to a list of terminals
in the call, then the goal corresponds to parsing List; if List is unbound in the call,
then the grammar is being used for generation.@REFILL

@item @b{expand_term}(T1, T2)
This predicate is used to transform terms that are read in, when a file is consulted or
compiled.  The usual use is to transform grammar rules into Prolog clauses: if T1 is a
grammar rule, then T2 is the corresponding Prolog clause.  Users may define their own
transformations by defining the predicate @b{term_expansion}/2.  When a term T1 is read in
when a file is being compiled or consulted, @b{expand_term}/2 first calls
@b{term_expansion}/2: if the expansion succeeds, the transformed term so obtained is used;
otherwise, if T1 is a grammar rule, then it is expanded using @b{dcg}/2; otherwise, T1 is
used as is.@REFILL

@item `C'(S1, Terminal, S2)
Used to handle terminal symbols in the expansion of grammar rules.  Not usually of direct
use to the user.  This is defined as:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{'C'([X|S], X, S).}
@end table

@node Profiling Programs, Utilities, Definite Clause Grammars, Top
@chapter Profiling Programs

There is an experimental utility for profiling programs interactively.  Two kinds of
profiling are supported: one may count the number of calls to a predicate, or compute the
time spent in a predicate.  It is important that the predicates being profiled are either
consulted, or compiled with the @code{t} option, so that calls to the relevant predicates can be
intercepted by the profiler.@REFILL

To use the profiler, predicates whose calls are to be counted must be passed to
@b{count}/1, e.g.@REFILL

@example
    | ?- count([p/1, q/2]), count(r/3).
@end example

@noindent
will set up ``count-points'' on the predicates @t{p}/1, @t{q}/2 and @t{r}/3.  Predicates whose calls
are to be timed have to be passed to @b{time}/1, e.g.@REFILL

@example
    | ?- time([s/1, t/2]), time(u/3).
@end example

@noindent
will set up ``time-points'' on the predicates @t{s}/1, @t{t}/2 and @t{u}/3.  It is possible to set
both count-points and time-points on the same predicate.  After count-points and
timepoints have been set, the program may be executed as many times as desired: the
profiling system will accumulate call counts and execution times for the appropriate
predicates.  Execution profiles may be obtained using the predicates @b{prof_stats}/0 or
@b{prof_stats}/1.  Using @b{prof_stats}/0 to display the execution profile will cause the
call counts and execution times of predicates being profiled to be reset to 0 (this may be
avoided by using @b{prof_stats}/1).@REFILL

It should be noted that in this context, the ``execution time'' for a predicate is an
estimate of the total time spent in the subtrees below calls to that predicate (including
failed subtrees): thus, the execution time figures may be dilated slightly if the subtree
below a timed predicate contains predicates that are being profiled, because of the time
taken for updating the call counts and execution times.  For each predicate, the execution
time is displayed as the fraction of time spent, in computation in subtrees under calls to
that predicate, relative to the time elapsed from the last time profiling was timed on or
the last time profiling statistics were taken, whichever was more recent.@REFILL

Bugs: May behave bizarrely if a predicate being profiled contains cuts.@REFILL

The following summarizes the library predicates supporting profiling:@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{count}(L)
Sets up a count-point on the predicates L, which causes calls to these predicates to be
counted, and turns profiling on.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is a predicate
symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L must be
instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call to
@b{count}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{time}(L)
Sets up a time-point on the predicates L, which causes execution times for calls to these
predicates to be accumulated, and turns profiling on.  L is either a term Pred/Arity,
where Pred is a predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented
as a list.  L must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the
time of the call to @b{time}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{nocount}(L)
Deletes the count-point on the predicates L.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is
a predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L
must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call
to @b{nocount}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{notime}(L)
Deletes the time-point on the predicates L.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is
a predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L
must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call
to @b{time}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{profiling}
Displays information about whether profile mode is on or not, and lists predicates that
have count- and time-points set on them.@REFILL

@item @b{prof_reset}(L)
Resets call counts and/or execution times for the predicates L.  L is either a term
Pred/Arity, where Pred is a predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms
represented as a list.  L must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it
defined, at the time of the call to @b{prof_reset}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{resetcount}(L)
Resets call counts for the predicates L.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is a
predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L
must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call
to @b{resetcount}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{resettime}(L)
Resets execution times for the predicates L.  L is either a term Pred/Arity, where Pred is
a predicate symbol and Arity its arity, or a set of such terms represented as a list.  L
must be instantiated, and the predicates specified in it defined, at the time of the call
to @b{resettime}/1.@REFILL

@item @b{profile}
Turns profiling on.  This causes subsequent execution of predicates with count- or
time-points to be profiled, and is a no-op if there are no such predicates.  The
predicates @b{count}/1 and @b{time}/1 cause profiling to be turned on
automatically.@REFILL

@item @b{noprofile}
Turns profiling off.  This causes count- and time-points to be ignored.@REFILL

@item @b{timepreds}(L)
Unifies L to a list of terms P/N where the predicate P of arity N has a time point set on
it.@REFILL

@item @b{countpreds}(L)
Unifies L to a list of terms P/N where the predicate P of arity N has a count point set on
it.@REFILL

@item @b{prof_stats}
Causes the call counts and/or execution times accumulated since the last call to
@b{prof_stats}/0 to be printed out for predicates that are being profiled.  The execution
times are given as fractions of the total time elapsed since the last time profiling was
turned on, or the last time @bb{prof_stats} was called, whichever was most recent.  This
also results in the call counts and relative execution times of these predicates being
reset to 0.  Equivalent to @b{prof_stats}(1).@REFILL

@item @b{prof_stats}(N)
Causes the call counts and/or execution times accumulated since the last call to
@b{prof_stats}/0 to be printed out for predicates that are being profiled.  The execution
times are given as fractions of the total time elapsed since the last time profiling was
turned on, or the last time @bb{prof_stats} was called, whichever was most recent.  If N is 1,
then this also results in the call counts and execution times of these predicates being
reset to 0; otherwise, the call counts and execution times are not reset.@REFILL
@end table

@node Utilities, Credits, Profiling Programs, Top
@chapter Other Library Utilities

The SB-Prolog library contains various other utilities, some of which are listed
below.@REFILL

@table @asis
@item @b{append}(X, Y, Z)
Succeeds if list Z is the concatenation of lists X and Y.@REFILL

@item @b{member}(X, L)
Checks whether X unifies with any element of list L, succeeding more than once if there
are multiple such elements.@REFILL

@item @b{$memberchk}(X, L)
Similar to @b{member}/2, except that @b{$memberchk}/2 is deterministic, i.e.  does not
succeed more than once for any call.@REFILL

@item @b{$reverse}(L, R)
Succeeds if R is the reverse of list L.  If L is not a fully determined list, i.e.  if the
tail of L is a variable, this predicate can succeed arbitrarily many
times.@REFILL

@item @b{$merge}(X, Y, Z)
Succeeds if Z is the list resulting from ``merging'' lists X and Y, i.e.  the elements of
X together with any element of Y not occurring in X.  If X or Y contain duplicates, Z may
also contain duplicates.@REFILL

@item @b{$absmember}(X, L)
Similar to @b{$member}/2, except that it checks for identity (through ==/2) rather than
unifiability (through =/2) of X with elements of L.@REFILL

@item @b{$nthmember}(X, L, N)
Succeeds if the N[th.] element of the list L unifies with X.  Fails if N is greater than
the length of L.  Either X and L, or L and N, should be instantiated at the time of the
call.@REFILL

@item @b{$member2}(X, L)
Checks whether X unifies with any of the actual elements of L.  The only difference
between this and @b{$member}/2 is on lists with a variable tail, e.g. @samp{[a,b,c|_]}:
while @b{$member}/2 would insert X at the end of such a list if it did not find it,
@b{$member2}/2 only checks for membership but does not insert it into the list if it is
not there.@REFILL

@item @b{length}(L, N)
Succeeds if the length of the list L is N.  This predicate is deterministic if L is
instantiated to a list of definite length, but is nondeterministic if L is a variable or
has a variable tail.@REFILL

@item @b{subsumes}(X, Y)
Succeeds if the term X subsumes the term Y (i.e. if Y is an instance of
X).@REFILL
@end table

