@node Efficiency, Adding Builtins, Index of Evaluable Predicates, Top
@appendix A Note on Coding for Efficiency

The SB-Prolog system tends to favour programs that are relatively pure.  Thus, for
example, asserts tend to be quite expensive, encouraging the user to avoid them if
possible.  This section points out some syntactic constructs that lead to the generation
of efficient code.  These involve (i) avoiding the creation of backtrack points; and (ii)
minimizing data movement between registers.  Optimization of logic programs is an area of
ongoing research, and we expect to enhance the capabilities of the system further in
future versions.@REFILL

@menu
* Avoiding Backtrack Points::
* Minimizing Data Movements::
* Processing Arguments::
* Testing Unifiability::
@end menu

@node Avoiding Backtrack Points, Minimizing Data Movement,, Efficiency
@section Avoiding Creation of Backtrack Points

Since the creation of backtrack points is relatively expensive, program efficiency may be
improved substantially by using constructs that avoid the creation of backtrack points
where possible.  The SB-Prolog compiler recognizes conditionals involving certain
complementary inline tests, and generates code that does not create choice points for such
cases.  Two inline tests p(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>) and q(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>) are
complementary if and only if:@REFILL

@tex
\gdef\EQUIV{$\equiv$}
@end tex
@iftex
@CENTER p(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>) @EQUIV{} not(q(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>)).
@end iftex
@ifinfo
@center p(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>) <==> not(q(t<1>, @dots{}, t<n>)).
@end ifinfo

For example, the literals `X > Y' and `X =< Y' are complementary.  At this point,
complementary tests are recognized as such only if their argument tuples are identical.
The inline predicates that are treated in this manner, with their corresponding
complementary literals, are shown in the table below:@REFILL

@ifinfo
            Inline Test    Complementary Test
                >/2            =</2
               =</2             >/2
               >=/2             </2
                </2            >=/2
              =:=/2           =\=/2
              =\=/2           =:=/2
               ?=/2            \=/2
               \=/2            ?=/2
              var/1        nonvar/1
           nonvar/1           var/1
@end ifinfo
@tex
\centerline{\vbox{\halign{\hfil#\hfil\quad&\quad\hfil#1\hfil\cr
Inline Test & Complementary Test\cr
$>$&${=}{<}$\cr
${=}{<}$&$>$\cr
${>}{=}$&$<$\cr
$<$&${>}{=}$\cr
${=}{:}{=}$&${=}{\rm\char`\\}{=}$\cr
${=}{\rm\char`\\}{=}$&${=}{:}{=}$\cr
${\rm?}{=}$&${\rm\char`\\}{=}$\cr
${\rm\char`\\}{=}$&${\rm?}{=}$\cr
{\bf var}&{\bf nonvar}\cr
{\bf nonvar}&{\bf var}\cr}}}
@end tex

The syntactic constructs recognized are:

@enumerate
@item
Disjuncts of the form:

@example
    head(@dots{}) :- ((test(t1,@dots{},tn),@dots{}) ; ((not(test(t1,@dots{},tn),@dots{})).
@r{or}
    head(@dots{}) :- ((test(t1,@dots{},tn),@dots{}) ; ((comp_test(t1,@dots{},tn),@dots{})).
@end example

@noindent
where test is one of the inline tests in the table above, and comp_test the corresponding
complementary test (note that the arguments to @code{test} and @code{comp_test} have to be
identical).@REFILL

@item
Conditionals of the form:

@example
    head :- (test<1>,@dots{},test<n>) -> @r{True_Case} ; @r{False_Case}.
@r{or}
    head :- (test<1>;@dots{};test<n>) -> @r{True_Case} ; @r{False_Case}.
@end example

@noindent
where each @code{test<i>} is an inline test, as mentioned in the table above.@REFILL

The code generated for these cases involves a test and conditional branch, and no choice
point is created.  We expect future versions of the translator to recognize a wider class
of complementary tests.@REFILL
@end enumerate

Notice that this discourages the use of explicit cuts.  For example, whereas a choice
point will be created for @REFILL

@example
    part(M,[E|L],U1,U2) :-
       ((E =< M, !, U1 = [E|U1a], U2 = U2a) ;
        (U1 = U1a, U2 = [E|U2a])),
       part(M,L,U1a,U2a).
@end example

@noindent
no choice point will be created for either:

@example
    part(M,[E|L],U1,U2) :-
       (E =< M ->
          (U1 = [E|U1a], U2 = U2a) ;
          (U1 = U1a, U2 = [E|U2a])),
       part(M,L,U1a,U2a).
@r{or}
    part(M,[E|L],U1,U2) :-
       ((E =< M, U1 = [E|U1a], U2 = U2a) ;
        (E > M,  U1 = U1a, U2 = [E|U2a])),
       part(M,L,U1a,U2a).
@end example

Thus, either of the two later versions will be more efficient than the version with the
explicit cut (this is a design decision we have consciously made, in the hope of
discouraging blatantly non-declarative code where efficient declarative code can be
written).@REFILL

@node Minimizing Data Movement, Processing Arguments, Avoiding Backtrack Points, Efficiency
@section Minimizing Data Movement Between Registers

Data movement between registers for parameter passing may be minimized by leaving variables
in the same argument position wherever possible.  Thus, the clause @REFILL

@CENTER p(X,Y) :- p1(X,Y,0).
@*is preferable to@*
@CENTER p(X,Y) :- p1(0,X,Y).

@noindent
because the first definition leaves the variables X and Y in the same argument positions
(first and second, respectively), while the second definition does not.@REFILL

@node Processing Arguments, Testing Unifiability, Minimizing Data Movement, Efficiency
@section Processing All Arguments of a Term

It is often the case that we wish to process each of the arguments of a term in turn.  For
example, to decide whether a compound term is ground, we have to check that each of its
arguments is ground.  One possibility is to create a list of those arguments, and traverse
the list processing each element.  Using this approach, a predicate to check for
groundness would be @REFILL

@example
    ground(T) :- atomic(T).
    ground(T) :- structure(T), T =.. [_|Args], groundargs(Args).
    groundargs([]).
    groundargs([A|ARest]) :- ground(A), groundargs(ARest).
@end example

This is not the most efficient way to process all the arguments of a term, because it
involves the creation of intermediate lists, which is expensive both in space and time.  A
much better alternative is to use @b{arg}/3 to index into the term and retrieve arguments.
Using this approach, the @t{ground}/1 predicate above would be written as:@REFILL

@example
    ground(T) :- atomic(T).
    ground(T) :- structure(T), functor(T,P,N), groundargs(1,N,T).
    groundargs(M,N,T) :-
       M =< N ->
          (arg(M,T,A), ground(A), M1 is M + 1, groundargs(M1,N,T)) ;
          true.
@end example

The second approach is likely to be more efficient than the first in SB-Prolog.

If the arguments of the term do not need to be processed in ascending order, then it is
more efficient to process them in descending order using @b{arg}/3 to access them.  For
example, the predicate for groundness checking could be written as:@REFILL

@example
    ground(T) :- atomic(T).
    ground(T) :- structure(T), functor(T, P, N), groundargs(N, T).
    groundargs(M,T) :-
       M =:= 0 ->
          true ;
          (arg(M,T,A), ground(A), M1 is M - 1, groundargs(M1,T)).
@end example

This is even more efficient than the earlier version, because (i) @code{groundargs} needs to have
one less parameter to be passed to it at each iteration; and (ii) testing @code{M =:= 0} is
simpler and more efficient than checking @code{M =< N}, and takes fewer machine
instructions.@REFILL

@node Testing Unifiability,, Processing Argument, Efficiency
@section Testing Unifiability

Often, it is necessary to check whether or not a term has a particular value.  If we know
that the term will be bound to a number, we can use the evaluable predicates =:=/2 or
=\=/2, as explained earlier.  For other values, it may often be cheaper, in the
appropriate circumstances, to use the predicates ?=/2 or \=/2.  For example, consider a
predicate @t{p}/2 that calls @t{q}/1 with its second argument if its first argument unifies with
@code{a}, and @t{r}/1 otherwise.  A naive definition might be:@REFILL

@example
    p(a, X) :- !, q(X).
    p(Y, X) :- r(X).
@end example

However, the call to @t{p}/2 results in the (temporary) creation of a backtrack point.  A
solution that avoids this backtrack point creation is:@REFILL

@example
    p(Y, X) :- Y ?= a -> q(X) ; r(X).
@end example

Of course, if the argument order in p/2 could be reversed in this case, then data movement
would be reduced even further (see above), and the code would be even more efficient:@REFILL

@example
    p(X, Y) :- Y ?= a -> q(X) ; r(X).
@end example

@node Adding Builtins,, Efficiency, Top
@appendix Adding Builtins to SB-Prolog

Adding a builtin involves writing the C code for the desired case and installing it into
the simulator.  The files in the directory @file{sim/builtin} contain the C code for the
builtin predicates supported by the system.  The following procedure is to be followed
when adding a builtin to the system:@REFILL

@enumerate
@item
Installing C Code:

@alphanumerate
@item
Go to the directory @file{sim/builtin}.

@item
Look at the @samp{#define}s in the file @file{builtin.h}, and choose a number @code{N1} (between
0 and 255) which is not in use to be the builtin number for the new
builtin.@REFILL

@item
Add to the file @file{builtin.h} the line

@example
    #define NEWBUILTIN N1
@end example

@item
The convention is that the code for builtin will be in a parameterless procedure named
@code{b_NEWBUILTIN}.  Modify the file @file{init_branch.c} in the directory @file{sim/builtin} by
adding these lines:@REFILL

@example
    extern int b_NEWBUILTIN();
@r{and}
    set_b_inst ( NEWBUILTIN, b_NEWBUILTIN );
@end example

@noindent
in the appropriate places.

@item
The builtins are compiled together into one object file, builtin.  Update the file
@file{Makefile} by appending the name of your object code file at the end of the line
``@t{OBJS = @dots{}}'' and insert the appropriate commands to compile your C source file,
e.g.:@REFILL

@example
    OBJS = [ @dots{} @i{other file names} @dots{} ] newbuiltin.o
    @dots{}
    newbuiltin.o: $(HS)
        cc $(CFLAGS) newbuiltin.c
@end example

@item
Execute the updated make file to create an updated object file
@file{builtin}.@REFILL

@item
Go to the directory @file{sim} and execute @code{make} to install the new file
@file{builtin}.@REFILL
@end alphanumerate

@item
Installing Prolog Code:

Assume that the builtin predicate to be added is @t{newbuiltin}/4.  The procedure for
installing the Prolog code for this is as follows:@REFILL

@alphanumerate
@item
Go to the SB-Prolog system directory @file{lib/src}, where the Prolog source for the
library routines is kept.@REFILL

@item
Each builtin definition is of the form

@CENTER pred@t{( @dots{} ) :- '_$builtin'(@r{N}).}

@noindent
where N is an integer, the builtin number of pred.

@item
Create a Prolog source file @file{newbuiltin.P} (notice correspondence with the name of
the predicate being defined) containing the definition:@REFILL

@CENTER @t{newbuiltin(A,B,C,D) :- '_$builtin'(N1).}

where @code{N1} is the builtin number of the predicate @code{newbuiltin}, obtained when
installing the C code for the builtin (see above).@REFILL

@item
Compile this Prolog predicate, using the simulator and the compile predicate, into a file
@file{newbuiltin} (notice correspondence with the name of the predicate being defined) in
the SB-Prolog directory @file{lib}.@REFILL
@end alphanumerate
@end enumerate

